# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: infection
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The genes coding for it are referred to as **16S rRNA genes** and are used in reconstructing phylogenies, due to the slow rates of evolution of this region of the gene.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Fox were two of the people who pioneered the use of 16S rRNA in phylogenetics in 1977.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Multiple sequences of the 16S rRNA gene can exist within a single bacterium.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The descriptor *16S* refers to the size of these ribosomal subunits as reflected indirectly by the speed at which they sediment when samples are centrifuged.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The 16S rRNA gene is used for phylogenetic studies as it is highly conserved between different species of bacteria and archaea.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Carl Woese pioneered this use of 16S rRNA in 1977.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] It is suggested that 16S rRNA gene can be used as a reliable molecular clock because 16S rRNA sequences from distantly related bacterial lineages are shown to have similar functionalities.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Some thermophilic archaea (e.g. order Thermoproteales) contain 16S rRNA gene introns that are located in highly conserved regions and can impact the annealing of "universal" primers.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Mitochondrial and chloroplastic rRNA are also amplified.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The most common primer pair was devised by Weisburg *et al.* (1991) and is currently referred to as 27F and 1492R; however, for some applications shorter amplicons may be necessary, for example for 454 sequencing with titanium chemistry the primer pair 27F-534R covering V1 to V3.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The two primers are almost identical, but 27F has an M instead of a C.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] AGAGTTTGATC**M**TGGCTCAG compared with 8F.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] In addition to highly conserved primer binding sites, 16S rRNA gene sequences contain hypervariable regions that can provide species-specific signature sequences useful for identification of bacteria.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] As a result, 16S rRNA gene sequencing has become prevalent in medical microbiology as a rapid and cheap alternative to phenotypic methods of bacterial identification.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Although it was originally used to identify bacteria, 16S sequencing was subsequently found to be capable of reclassifying bacteria into completely new species, or even genera.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] It has also been used to describe new species that have never been successfully cultured.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] With third-generation sequencing coming to many labs, simultaneous identification of thousands of 16S rRNA sequences is possible within hours, allowing metagenomic studies, for example of gut flora.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] In samples collected from patients with confirmed infections, 16S rRNA next-generation sequencing (NGS) demonstrated enhanced detection in 40% of cases compared to traditional culture methods; moreover, pre-sampling antibiotic consumption did not significantly affect the sensitivity of 16S NGS.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The bacterial 16S gene contains nine hypervariable regions (V1–V9), ranging from about 30 to 100 base pairs long, that are involved in the secondary structure of the small ribosomal subunit.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The degree of conservation varies widely between hypervariable regions, with more conserved regions correlating to higher-level taxonomy and less conserved regions to lower levels, such as genus and species.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] While the entire 16S sequence allows for comparison of all hypervariable regions, at approximately 1,500 base pairs long it can be prohibitively expensive for studies seeking to identify or characterize diverse bacterial communities.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] These studies commonly utilize the Illumina platform, which produces reads at rates 50-fold and 12,000-fold less expensive than 454 pyrosequencing and Sanger sequencing, respectively.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] While cheaper and allowing for deeper community coverage, Illumina sequencing only produces reads 75–250 base pairs long (up to 300 base pairs with Illumina MiSeq), and has no established protocol for reliably assembling the full gene in community samples.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Full hypervariable regions can be assembled from a single Illumina run, however, making them ideal targets for the platform.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] While 16S hypervariable regions can vary dramatically between bacteria, the 16S gene as a whole maintains greater length homogeneity than its eukaryotic counterpart (18S ribosomal RNA), which can make alignments easier.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Additionally, the 16S gene contains highly conserved sequences between hypervariable regions, enabling the design of universal primers that can reliably produce the same sections of the 16S sequence across different taxa.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Although no hypervariable region can accurately classify all bacteria from domain to species, some can reliably predict specific taxonomic levels.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Many community studies select semi-conserved hypervariable regions like the V4 for this reason, as it can provide resolution at the phylum level as accurately as the full 16S gene.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] While lesser-conserved regions struggle to classify new species when higher order taxonomy is unknown, they are often used to detect the presence of specific pathogens.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] In one study by Chakravorty et al. in 2007, the authors characterized the V1–V8 regions of a variety of pathogens in order to determine which hypervariable regions would be most useful to include for disease-specific and broad assays.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Amongst other findings, they noted that the V3 region was best at identifying the genus for all pathogens tested, and that V6 was the most accurate at differentiating species between all CDC-watched pathogens tested, including anthrax.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] While 16S hypervariable region analysis is a powerful tool for bacterial taxonomic studies, it struggles to differentiate between closely related species.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] In the families *Enterobacteriaceae*, *Clostridiaceae*, and *Peptostreptococcaceae*, species can share up to 99% sequence similarity across the full 16S gene.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] As a result, the V4 sequences can differ by only a few nucleotides, leaving reference databases unable to reliably classify these bacteria at lower taxonomic levels.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] By limiting 16S analysis to select hypervariable regions, these studies can fail to observe differences in closely related taxa and group them into single taxonomic units, therefore underestimating the total diversity of the sample.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, bacterial genomes can house multiple 16S genes, with the V1, V2, and V6 regions containing the greatest intraspecies diversity.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] While not the most precise method of classifying bacterial species, analysis of the hypervariable regions remains one of the most useful tools available to bacterial community studies.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Under the assumption that evolution is driven by vertical transmission, 16S rRNA genes have long been believed to be species-specific, and infallible as genetic markers inferring phylogenetic relationships among prokaryotes.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] However, a growing number of observations suggest the occurrence of horizontal transfer of these genes.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] In addition to observations of natural occurrence, transferability of these genes is supported experimentally using a specialized *Escherichia coli* genetic system.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Using a null mutant of *E. coli* as host, growth of the mutant strain was shown to be complemented by foreign 16S rRNA genes that were phylogenetically distinct from *E. coli* at the phylum level.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Such functional compatibility was also seen in *Thermus thermophilus*.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, in *T. thermophilus*, both complete and partial gene transfer was observed.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Partial transfer resulted in spontaneous generation of apparently random chimera between host and foreign bacterial genes.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Thus, 16S rRNA genes may have evolved through multiple mechanisms, including vertical inheritance and horizontal gene transfer; the frequency of the latter may be much higher than previously thought.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The 16S rRNA gene is used as the standard for classification and identification of microbes, because it is present in most microbes and shows proper changes.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Type strains of 16S rRNA gene sequences for most bacteria and archaea are available on public databases, such as NCBI.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] However, the quality of the sequences found on these databases is often not validated.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Therefore, secondary databases that collect only 16S rRNA sequences are widely used.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] SILVA provides comprehensive, quality checked and regularly updated datasets of aligned small (16S/18S, SSU) and large subunit (23S/28S, LSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences for all three domains of life as well as a suite of search, primer-design and alignment tools (Bacteria, Archaea and Eukarya).
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] GreenGenes is a quality controlled, comprehensive 16S rRNA gene reference database and taxonomy based on a *de novo* phylogeny that provides standard operational taxonomic unit sets.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] EzBioCloud database, formerly known as EzTaxon, consists of a complete hierarchical taxonomic system containing 62,988 bacteria and archaea species/phylotypes which includes 15,290 valid published names as of September 2018.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Based on the phylogenetic relationship such as maximum-likelihood and OrthoANI, all species/subspecies are represented by at least one 16S rRNA gene sequence.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The EzBioCloud database is systematically curated and updated regularly which also includes novel candidate species.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Moreover, the website provides bioinformatics tools such as ANI calculator, ContEst16S and 16S rRNA DB for QIIME and Mothur pipeline.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] MIMt is a compact non-redundant 16S database for a rapid metagenomic samples identification.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] It is composed of 48,749 full 16S sequences belonging to 24,626 well classified bacteria and archaea species.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] All sequences were obtained from complete genomes deposited in NCBI and for each of the sequences full taxonomic hierarchy is provided.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] It contains no redundancy, so only one representative for each species was considered avoiding same sequences from different strains, isolates or pathovars resulting in a very fast tool for microorganisms identification, compatible with any classification software (QIIME, Mothur, DADA, etc).
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The Ribosomal Database Project (RDP) was a curated database that offers ribosome data along with related programs and services.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The offerings included phylogenetically ordered alignments of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences, derived phylogenetic trees, rRNA secondary structure diagrams and various software packages for handling, analyzing and displaying alignments and trees.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] Due to its large size the RDP database is often used as the basis for bioinformatic tool development and creating manually curated databases.
[src:infection/16s-ribosomal-rna] The RDP server was taken offline in 2023, but the software is still available for download.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The key event at the conference was the presentation of data from the Vaccine Safety Datalink examining the possibility of a link between the mercury compound thimerosol in vaccines and neurological problems in children who had received those vaccines.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Kennedy, Jr., published by *Rolling Stone* and Salon.com, focused on the Simpsonwood meeting as part of a conspiracy to withhold or falsify vaccine-safety information.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] However, Kennedy's article contained numerous major factual errors and, after a number of corrections, was ultimately retracted by Salon.com.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Nonetheless, on the basis of Kennedy's claims, the conference gained notoriety in the anti-vaccination movement.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The conference was convened following a resolution by the Congress of the United States in 1997 requiring the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to review the thimerosal content of approved drugs and biologics.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Three vaccines of primary interest were discussed: hepatitis B vaccine, DPT vaccine, and the Hib vaccine.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Attendees included experts in the fields of autism, pediatrics, toxicology, epidemiology and vaccines.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Also in attendance were approximately half a dozen public-health organisations and pharmaceutical companies, as well as eleven consultants to the CDC, a rapporteur, and a statistician.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The meeting served as a prelude to vaccine policy meetings held by the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP), which sets U.S. vaccine policy for the CDC.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The session was also to serve as the initial meeting of the ACIP work group on thimerosal and immunization.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Presentations and supporting documents from the conference were subject to a news embargo until June 21, 2000, at which point they were published by the ACIP.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] After the conference, researchers carried out a planned second phase to further analyze and clarify the study's preliminary findings.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The results of this second analysis were published in 2003.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The June 20, 2005, issue of *Rolling Stone* contained an article written by Robert F.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Kennedy, Jr., entitled "Deadly Immunity".
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The article, which was also published on Salon.com, focused on the Simpsonwood conference, and alleged that government and private industry had colluded to "thwart the Freedom of Information Act" and "withhold" vaccine-safety findings from the public.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Salon.com later said that the errors in the article "went far in undermining Kennedy’s exposé", and corrected it on five occasions.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] The publisher later retracted it in January 2011, stating that criticisms of the article and flaws in the science connecting autism and vaccines undermined its value.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] By the time the final study results discussed at Simpsonwood were published in 2003, the lead researcher, Thomas Verstraeten, had gone to work for GlaxoSmithKline.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Kennedy contended that the delay in publication gave Verstraeten sufficient time to fix the data around the CDC's alleged objective of obscuring a link between thimerosal and autism.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Verstraeten denied the allegations, and published an account of the matter in the journal *Pediatrics*.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions rejected allegations of impropriety against Verstraeten and the CDC.
[src:infection/2000-simpsonwood-cdc-conference] Addressing Kennedy's statements, the Committee found that: "Instead of hiding the [Simpsonwood] data or restricting access to it, CDC distributed it, often to individuals who had never seen it before, and solicited outside opinion regarding how to interpret it.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The **2009 swine flu pandemic vaccines** were influenza vaccines developed to protect against the pandemic H1N1/09 virus.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] These vaccines either contained inactivated (killed) influenza virus, or weakened live virus that could not cause influenza.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The killed virus was injected, while the live virus was given as a nasal spray.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Both these types of vaccine were produced by growing the virus in chicken eggs.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Around three billion doses were produced, with delivery in November 2009.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In studies, the vaccines appeared both effective and safe, providing a strong protective immune response and having a similar safety profile to the usual seasonal influenza vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] However, about 30% of people already had some immunity to the virus, with the vaccine conferring greatest benefit on young people, since many older people are already immune through exposure to similar viruses in the past.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The vaccine also provided some cross-protection against the 1918 flu pandemic strain.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Developing, testing, and manufacturing sufficient quantities of a vaccine is a process that takes many months.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] TIV works by putting into the bloodstream those parts of three strains of flu virus that the body uses to create antibodies; while LAIV works by inoculating the body with those same three strains, but in a modified form that cannot cause illness.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] LAIV is not recommended for individuals under age 2 or over age 49, but might be comparatively more effective among children over age two.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] For the inactivated vaccines, the virus is grown by injecting it, along with some antibiotics, into fertilized chicken eggs.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] About one to two eggs are needed to make each dose of vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The virus replicates within the allantois of the embryo, which is the equivalent of the placenta in mammals.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The fluid in this structure is removed and the virus purified from this fluid by methods such as filtration or centrifugation.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The purified viruses are then inactivated ("killed") with a small amount of a disinfectant.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The inactivated virus is treated with detergent to break up the virus into particles, and the broken capsule segments and released proteins are concentrated by centrifugation.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The final preparation is suspended in sterile phosphate buffered saline ready for injection.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This vaccine mainly contains the killed virus but might also contain tiny amounts of egg protein and the antibiotics, disinfectant and detergent used in the manufacturing process.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In multi-dose versions of the vaccine, the preservative thimerosal is added to prevent growth of bacteria.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In some versions of the vaccine used in Europe and Canada, such as *Arepanrix* and *Fluad*, an adjuvant is also added, this contains squalene, vitamin E and an emulsifier called polysorbate 80.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] To make the live vaccine, the virus is first adapted to grow at 25 °C (77 °F) and then grown at this temperature until it loses the ability to cause illness in humans, which requires the virus to grow at normal human body temperature of 37 °C (99 °F).
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Multiple mutations are needed for the virus to grow at cold temperatures, so this process is effectively irreversible and once the virus has lost virulence (become "attenuated"), it will not regain the ability to infect people.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The attenuated virus is then grown in chicken eggs as before.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The virus-containing fluid is harvested and the virus purified by filtration; this step also removes any contaminating bacteria.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The filtered preparation is then diluted into a solution that stabilizes the virus.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This solution contains monosodium glutamate, potassium phosphate, gelatin, the antibiotic gentamicin, and sugar.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A different method of producing influenza virus was used to produce the Novartis vaccine Optaflu.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In this vaccine the virus is grown in cell culture instead of in eggs.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This method is faster than the classic egg-based system and produces a purer final product.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] There are no traces of egg proteins in the final product, so it is safe for people with egg allergies.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Prior to the H1N1/09 outbreak, WHO recommended that vaccines for the Northern Hemisphere's 2009–2010 flu season contain an A(H1N1)-like virus, and stocks were made available.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] However, the strain of H1N1 in the seasonal flu vaccine was different from the pandemic strain H1N1/09 and offered no immunity against it.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) characterized over 80 new H1N1 viruses that may be used in a vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Seasonal flu vaccine was being made as of May 2009.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Although vaccine makers would be ready to switch to making a swine flu vaccine, many questions remained unanswered, including: "Should we really make a swine flu vaccine?
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Should we base a vaccine on the current virus, since flu viruses change rapidly?
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Vaccine against the current virus might be far less effective against a changed virus – should we wait to see if the virus changes?
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The costs of producing a vaccine also became an issue, with some U.S. lawmakers questioning whether a new vaccine was worth the unknown benefits.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Representatives Phil Gingrey and Paul Broun, for instance, were not convinced that the U.S. should spend up to US$2 billion to produce one, with Gingrey stating "We can't let all of our spending and our reaction be media-driven in responding to a panic so that we don't get Katrina-ed. ...
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Before the pandemic was declared, the WHO said that if a pandemic was declared it would attempt to make sure that a substantial amount of vaccine was available for the benefit of developing countries.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Vaccine makers and countries with standing orders, such as the U.S. and a number of European countries, would be asked, according to WHO officials, "to share with developing countries from the moment the first batches are ready if an H1N1 vaccine is made" for a pandemic strain.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The global body stated that it wanted companies to donate at least 10% of their production or offer reduced prices for poor countries that could otherwise be left without vaccines if there is a sudden surge in demand.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] After a meeting with the WHO on 14 May 2009, pharmaceutical companies said they were ready to begin making a swine flu vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] According to news reports, the WHO's experts would present recommendations to WHO Director-General Margaret Chan, who was expected to issue advice to vaccine manufacturers and the Sixty-second World Health Assembly.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] WHO's Keiji Fukuda told reporters "These are enormously complicated questions, and they are not something that anyone can make in a single meeting." Most flu vaccine companies can not make both seasonal flu vaccine and pandemic flu vaccine at the same time.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Production takes months and it is impossible to switch halfway through if health officials make a mistake.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] If the swine flu mutates, scientists aren't sure how effective a vaccine made now from the current strain will remain.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Rather than wait on the WHO decision, however, some countries in Europe have decided to go ahead with early vaccine orders.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] On 20 May 2009, AP reported: "Manufacturers won't be able to start making the [swine flu] vaccine until mid-July at the earliest, weeks later than previous predictions, according to an expert panel convened by WHO.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] It will then take months to produce the vaccine in large quantities.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Another option proposed by the CDC was an "earlier rollout of seasonal vaccine," according to the CDC's Daniel Jernigan.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] He said the CDC would work with vaccine manufacturers and experts to see if that would be possible and desirable.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Flu vaccination usually starts in September in the United States and peaks in November.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Some vaccine experts agree it would be better to launch a second round of vaccinations against the new H1N1 strain instead of trying to add it to the seasonal flu vaccine or replacing one of its three components with the new H1N1 virus.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The Australian company CSL said that they were developing a vaccine for the swine flu and predicted that a suitable vaccine would be ready by August.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] However, John Sterling, Editor in Chief of *Genetic Engineering & Biotechnology News*, said on 2 June, "It can take five or six months to come up with an entirely novel influenza vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] As of September 2009, a vaccine for H1N1/09 was expected to be available starting in November 2009, with production of three billion doses per year.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] It was expected that two doses would be needed to provide sufficient protection, but tests indicated that one dose would be sufficient for adults.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] As of 28 September 2009, GlaxoSmithKline produced a vaccine made by growing the virus in hens' eggs, then breaking and deactivating the virus, and Baxter International produced a vaccine made in cell culture, suitable for those who have an egg allergy.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The vaccines have been approved for use in the European Union.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Initial Phase I human testing began with Novartis' MF59 candidate in July 2009, at which time phase II trials of CSL's candidate CSL425 vaccine were planned to start in August 2009, but had not begun recruiting.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Sanofi Pasteur's candidate inactivated H1N1 had several phase II trials planned as of 21 July 2009, but had not begun recruiting.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] News coverage conflicted with this information, as Australian trials of the CSL candidate were announced as having started on 21 July, and the Chinese government announced the start of trials of the Hualan Biological Engineering candidate.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In July 2009, Omninvest in Hungary, in a randomized-controlled trial, began testing Fluval P, a whole virion, aluminum adjuvanted pandemic influenza H1N1 vaccine, which was found to be safe and effective, when administered alone, or together with the seasonal influenza vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Pandemrix, made by GlaxoSmithKline (GSK), and Focetria, made by Novartis were approved by the European Medicines Agency on 25 September 2009, and Celvapan, made by Baxter was approved the following week.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The first comparative clinical study of both vaccines started on children in the United Kingdom on 25 September 2009.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] GSK announced results from clinical trials assessing the use of Pandemrix in children, adults, and the elderly.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A 2009 trial examined the safety and efficacy of two different doses of the split-virus vaccine, and was published in *The New England Journal of Medicine*.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The vaccine used in the trial was prepared by CSL Biotherapies in chicken eggs, in the same way as the seasonal vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A robust immune response was produced in over 90% of patients after a single dose of either 15 or 30 μg of antigen.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This study suggested that the current recommendation for two doses of vaccine are overkill and that a single dose is quite sufficient.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Arepanrix, an AS03-Adjuvanted H1N1 Pandemic Influenza Vaccine similar to Pandemrix and also made by GSK, was authorized by Canada's Minister of Health on 21 October 2009.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] National Institutes of Health (NIH) concluded that the 2009 H1N1 ("swine flu") vaccine has a safety profile similar to that of seasonal vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In an initial clinical trial in Australia, non-serious adverse events were reported by about half of the 240 people vaccinated, with these events including tenderness and pain at the site of injection, headache, malaise, and muscle pain.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Two people had more severe events, with a much longer spell of nausea, muscle pain and malaise that lasted several days.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The authors stated that the frequency and severity of these adverse events were similar to those normally seen with seasonal influenza vaccines.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A second trial involved 2,200 people ranging from 3 to 77 years of age.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In this study no patients reported serious adverse events, with the most commonly observed events being pain at the injection site and fever, which occurred in 10–25% of people.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Although this trial followed up patients individually, the Government has been criticized for relying on voluntary reporting for post-vaccination evaluation in other circumstances, since this is "unlikely to accurately measure the percentage of people who get adverse effect".
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] As of 19 November 2009, the World Health Organization (WHO) said that 65 million doses of vaccine had been administered and that it had a similar safety profile to the seasonal flu vaccine, with no significant differences in the adverse events produced by the different types of vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] There has been one report of an adverse event per 10,000 doses of vaccine, with only five percent of these adverse events being serious, an overall rate of serious events of one in 200,000 doses.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In Canada, after 6.6 million doses of vaccine had been distributed between 21 October and 7 November, there were reports of mild adverse events in 598 people vaccinated including: nausea, dizziness, headache, fever, vomiting, and swelling or soreness at the injection site.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] There were reports of tingling lips or tongue, difficulty breathing, hives, and skin rashes.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Thirty six people had serious adverse events, including anaphylaxis and febrile convulsions.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The rate of serious adverse events is one in 200,000 doses distributed, which according to Canada's chief public health officer, is less than expected for the seasonal flu vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] GlaxoSmithKline recalled a batch of vaccine in Canada after it appeared to cause higher rates of adverse events than other batches.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In the USA, 46 million doses had been distributed as of 20 November 2009, and 3182 adverse events were reported.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The CDC stated that the "vast majority" were mild, with about one serious adverse event in 260,000 doses.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In Japan, around 15 million people had been vaccinated by 31 December 2009.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] 1,900 cases of side effects and 104 cases of death were reported from medical institutions.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The health ministry announced that it will conduct epidemiologic investigation.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In France, around five million people had been vaccinated by 30 December 2009.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] 2,657 cases of side effects, eight cases of intrauterine death and five cases of miscarriages were reported after vaccination by afssaps.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Rare potential adverse events are temporary bleeding disorders and Guillain–Barré syndrome (GBS), a serious condition involving the peripheral nervous system, from which most patients recover fully within a few months to a year.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Some studies have indicated that influenza-like illness is itself associated with an increased risk of GBS, suggesting that vaccination might indirectly protect against the disorder by protecting against flu.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] According to Marie-Paule Kieny of WHO assessing the side-effects of large-scale influenza vaccination is complicated by the fact that in any large population a few people will become ill and die at any time.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Some scientists have reported concerns about the longer-term effects of the vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] For instance, Sucharit Bhakdi, professor of medical microbiology at the Johannes Gutenberg University of Mainz in Germany, wrote in the journal, *Medical Microbiology and Immunology*, of the possibility that immune stimulation by vaccines or any other cause might worsen pre-existing heart disease.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Chris Shaw, a neuroscientist at the University of British Columbia, expressed concern that serious side-effects may not appear immediately; he said it took five to ten years to see most of the Gulf War syndrome outcomes.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Squalene-based adjuvants have been used in European influenza vaccines since 1997, with about 22 million doses administered over the past twelve years.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The WHO states that no severe side effects have been associated with these vaccines, although they can produce mild inflammation at the site of injection.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The safety of squalene-containing influenza vaccines have also been tested in two separate clinical trials, one with healthy non-elderly people, and one with elderly people, in both trials the vaccine was safe and well tolerated, with only weak side-effects, such as mild pain at the injection site.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A 2009 meta-analysis brought together data from 64 clinical trials of influenza vaccines with the squalene-containing adjuvant MF59 and compared them to the effects of vaccines with no adjuvant.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A paper published in 2000 suggested that squalene might have caused of Gulf War syndrome by producing anti-squalene antibodies, although other scientists stated that it was uncertain if the methods used were actually capable of detecting these antibodies.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Furthermore, none of the vaccines given to US troops during the Gulf war actually contained any squalene adjuvants.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Multi-dose versions of the vaccine contain the preservative thiomersal (also known as thimerosal), a mercury compound that prevents contamination when the vial is used repeatedly.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Single-dose versions and the live vaccine do not contain this preservative.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In the U.S., one dose from a multi-dose vial contains approximately 25 micrograms of mercury, a bit less than a typical tuna fish sandwich.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] (The comparison of the injected and ingested quantities is for reference only, since the rate of absorption of ingested elemental mercury into the bloodstream is less than 0.01%.) In Canada, different variants contain five and 50 micrograms of thimerosal per dose.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The use of thiomersal has been controversial, with claims that it can cause autism and other developmental disorders.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Institute of Medicine examined these claims and concluded in 2004 that the evidence did not support any link between vaccines and autism.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] National Health Service stated in 2003 that "There is no evidence of long-term adverse effects due to the exposure levels of thiomersal in vaccines." The World Health Organization concluded that there is "no evidence of toxicity in infants, children or adults exposed to thiomersal in vaccines".
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In 2008 a review noted that even though thiomersal was removed from all US childhood vaccines in 2001, this has not changed the number of autism diagnoses, which are still increasing.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] According to the CDC, there is no evidence either for or against dystonia being caused by the vaccinations.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] Due to the very low numbers of cases, dystonia is poorly understood.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] There were only five cases noted that might have been associated with influenza vaccinations over a span of eighteen years.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In one discredited case, a woman wrongly blamed difficulties with movement and speech on a seasonal influenza vaccination.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The Dystonia Medical Research Foundation stated that it is unlikely that the symptoms in this case were actually dystonia and stated that there has "never been a validated case of dystonia resulting from a flu shot".
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] A vaccine court special master concluded that the woman's symptoms weren't from the vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] On 15 December 2009, one of the five manufacturers supplying the H1N1 vaccine to the United States recalled thousands of doses because they were not as potent as expected.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The French manufacturer Sanofi Pasteur voluntarily recalled about 800,000 doses of vaccine meant for children between the ages of six months and 35 months.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The company and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) emphasized that the recall was not prompted by safety concerns, and that even though the vaccine is not quite as potent as it is supposed to be, children who received it do not need to be immunized again.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The CDC emphasized that there is no danger for any child who received the recalled vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] When asked what parents should do, CDC spokesman Tom Skinner said, "absolutely nothing." He said if children receive this vaccine, they will be fine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In 2010, The Swedish Medical Products Agency (MPA) and The Finnish National Institute for Health and Welfare (THL) received reports from Swedish and Finnish health care professionals regarding narcolepsy as suspected adverse reaction following Pandemrix flu vaccination.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The reports concern children aged 12–16 years where symptoms compatible with narcolepsy, diagnosed after thorough medical investigation, have occurred one to two months after vaccination.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] THL concluded in February 2011 that there is a clear connection between the Pandemrix vaccination campaign of 2009 and 2010 and narcolepsy epidemic in Finland: there was a nine times higher probability to get narcolepsy with vaccination than without it.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] This excludes the large majority of individuals aged six months to 24 years, a group for which the CDC recommends vaccination.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The United Kingdom began its administration program 21 October 2009.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] UK Soldiers serving in Afghanistan will also be offered vaccination.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] By April 2010, it was apparent that most of the vaccine was not needed.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The US government had bought 229 million doses of H1N1 vaccines of which 91 million doses were used; of the surplus, 5 million doses were stored in bulk, 15 million doses were sent to developing countries and 71 million doses were destroyed.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] The World Health Organization is planning to examine if it overreacted to the H1N1 outbreak.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] General political issues, not restricted to the 2009 outbreak, arose regarding the distribution of vaccine.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] In the case of a lethal pandemic people will be demanding access to the vaccine and the major problem will be making it available to those who need it.
[src:infection/2009-swine-flu-pandemic-vaccine] While it has been suggested that compulsory vaccination may be needed to control a pandemic, many countries do not have a legal framework that would allow this.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] The **2020–21 Singapore circuit breaker measures** were a stay-at-home order and *cordon sanitaire* implemented as a preventive measure by the Government of Singapore in response to the COVID-19 pandemic in the country on 7 April 2020.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] The measures were brought into legal effect by the Minister for Health with the COVID-19 (Temporary Measures) (Control Order) Regulations 2020, published on 7 April 2020.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Singapore had relatively few COVID-19 cases before the emergence of the Delta and Omicron variants from 8 May 2021 to 29 March 2022.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] With its relative success in curbing the early spread of the virus in Singapore, the term "circuit breaker" and its measures was subsequently adopted by other countries, particularly in Canada and the United Kingdom.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Singapore recorded its first COVID-19 case on 23 January 2020.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] With that, many Singaporeans have purchased and worn masks when not at home; practiced social distancing and on 7 February 2020, Singapore raised the Disease Outbreak Response System Condition (DORSCON) level from Yellow to Orange in response to additional local cases of uncertain origin.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] On 24 March, the Multi-Ministry Task Force announced stricter measures to combat the spread of COVID-19, after a huge spike in cases originating from returning Singaporeans in the community.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] These measures include the closure of entertainment venues, tuition and enrichment centres and places of worship.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Malls, retail establishments and tourist attractions were required to reduce their crowd density to stay open.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Gatherings of more than 10 people outside work and school are prohibited.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] On 3 April 2020, Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong announced a nationwide partial lockdown, known as a *circuit breaker*, to contain the spread of COVID-19 in Singapore.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] These measures came after an increase of unlinked cases over the preceding month, as well as the risk of a huge cluster of infections.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Most of the workplaces were converted to remote work as default during the lockdown and schools were transitioned to home-based learning thereafter.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] As dining-in is a high-risk activity; all food establishments were only allowed to offer take-away, drive-thru and delivery of food.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Non-essential advertising at shopping centres are not allowed to be shown or advertised and only advertising from essential service offers and safe management measures such as mask wearing and social distancing are allowed.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Social gatherings of any size, in homes or public spaces such as parks and Housing Board void decks, were also banned.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] These measures only took effect from 7 April 2020 to 1 June 2020, 16 May 2021 to 13 June 2021 and 22 July 2021 to 9 August 2021.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] On 14 April, Minister for National Development Lawrence Wong announced that the wearing of masks became compulsory when not at home with immediate effect, with fines and prosecution for offenders who refuse to do so.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] After discovering that the unknown number of cases was greater than expected, Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong announced on 21 April an extension of the circuit breaker to 1 June.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Popular markets used an odd/even date entry restriction; ID ending with odd numbers are only allowed entry on odd dates of the month and ID ending with even numbers are only allowed entry on even dates on the month.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] On 21 April, the Ministry of Education brought forward the 4-week school holidays for all MOE Kindergartens, primary, secondary and Pre-University students, which are usually held in June, to May.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Institutes of Higher Learning extended their Home-based Learning.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] The Singapore franchise of McDonald's also shut all of its restaurants islandwide, as a response to a number of its employees being infected.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Some restrictions were relaxed progressively in stages to prepare for the end of the circuit breaker on 1 June.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) shops and essential condo activities were allowed to reopen on 5 May, followed by businesses like home-based bakeries, some food shops, barbers (only basic haircuts), manufacturing of confectionery, and laundry shops on 12 May.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Schools resumed face-to-face lessons for smaller groups in graduating cohorts and those requiring urgent assistance on 19 May.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] On 8 May, the MOH announced that all TCM shops are allowed to sell retail products again from 12 May, after receiving feedback from seniors that travelling to the initially allowed 130 TCM medical halls was too far for them.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] The Ministry of Health mandated the use of SafeEntry and TraceTogether, which is also called *TraceTogether-only SafeEntry* (TT-only SE) during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Scanning in/out using the *TraceTogether-only SafeEntry* (TT-only SE) either through the TraceTogether app or token was made mandatory for all Singaporeans and at all places such as cinemas, restaurants, workplaces, schools and shopping malls for contact tracing purposes.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] These included the device called SafeEntry Gateway (Check in and check out) to enable users to scan in and out.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] In addition, TraceTogether also showed vaccination status and pre-event testing (PET) status whether the person test positive or negative for COVID-19.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Tokens could be collected from the community centres and vending machines.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Earlier in 2020, three planned phases of reopening were announced, which were part of a wider zero-COVID effort.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] These phases ended on 8 May 2021 because of the Delta variant.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Restrictions due to new Variants of Concern (Delta and Omicron) started on 8 May 2021 and ended on 29 March 2022, during which gatherings of more than five people were prohibited.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Two separate lockdowns ran from 16 May 2021 to 13 June 2021 and 23 July to 9 August 2021, but in between 14 June 2021 and 23 July 2021, the government only allowed a reopening similar to Phase 1 of June 2020.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] The government then changed the reopening plan to only allow vaccinated persons to use certain services from August 2021.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] In addition, it was announced on 14 December 2020 that the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine was approved for use in Singapore, with the first batch slated for around end of December 2020.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] On 3 February 2021, the Moderna vaccine was approved for use in Singapore, with the first batch arriving around March 2021.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Subsequent batches for both vaccines were planned to arrive throughout 2021.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] A successful mass vaccination campaign was launched that achieved very high vaccination rate.
[src:infection/2020-21-singapore-circuit-breaker-measures] Through 2021, there were several high-profile instances of people, such as Phoon Chiu Yoke, refusing to abide by the circuit breaker regulations.
[src:infection/abc-clio] ABC-Clio provides service to fifteen different online databases which contain over one million online textbooks.
[src:infection/abc-clio] The company consults academic leaders in the fields they cover in order to provide authority for their reference titles.
[src:infection/abc-clio] The headquarters are located in Santa Barbara, California.
[src:infection/abc-clio] ABC-Clio was founded in 1955 as a privately held corporation by Eric Boehm with its first publication, *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:infection/abc-clio] The name represents the company's two original divisions when it incorporated in 1969: ABC stands for American Bibliographical Center and Clio Press is named after Clio, the muse of history from ancient Greek mythology.
[src:infection/abc-clio] According to Boehm, he had always been interested in history so when he noticed that there were not many good historical abstracting services available, he started publishing the *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:infection/abc-clio] During the 1960s, a sister bibliographic and abstract publication on American history was added, *America: History and Life*, which was considered an award-winning title.
[src:infection/abc-clio] The company entered into digital publishing with electronic data in the 1960s and in 1975, it published its first online database called *DIALOG*.
[src:infection/abc-clio] During the 1980s, ABC-Clio expanded into providing primary reference books such as encyclopedias and dictionaries and stopped publishing bibliographic books.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In the 1990s, ABC-Clio began to provide access to its humanities database on CD-ROM.
[src:infection/abc-clio] The *Exegy Current Events* CD-ROM was named "Best Disc of the Year" by Library Journal.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In 1998, ABC-Clio provided electronic access to *America: History and Life*.
[src:infection/abc-clio] By the 2000s, one of the company's most popular products had become online databases for researching many topics in the field of the humanities.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In 2001, ABC-Clio began to publish eBooks, initially providing 150 different titles to schools and libraries.
[src:infection/abc-clio] The company's reference books had won numerous awards, and the company started a series of subject-related online databases for secondary school use.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In 2004, the company acquired the quarterly historical journal, *Journal of the West*, which has been published since 1962.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In 1996, ABC-Clio merged with an electronic publishing company, Intellimation, which also produced educational software.
[src:infection/abc-clio] The merger brought Becky Snyder, who by 2009 had become ABC-Clio's president, from Intellimation.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In 2007, it sold two databases – *Historical Abstracts* and *America: History and Life* – to EBSCO Publishing; in addition, the companies also agreed a partnership through which nine additional ABC-Clio databases would be distributed through EBSCO Publishing.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing acquired ABC-Clio for US$22.9 million (equivalent to $26.1 million in 2024).
[src:infection/abc-clio] In 2008, ABC-Clio acquired the Greenwood Publishing Group from Houghton Mifflin Harcourt.
[src:infection/abc-clio] The deal gave ABC-Clio a "perpetual license" to use the imprints of Greenwood Press and publish all of its titles.
[src:infection/abc-clio] Acquiring the publishing group gave ABC-Clio access to Greenwood Press, Praeger Publishers, Praeger Security International, and Libraries Unlimited.
[src:infection/abc-clio] Greenwood focuses on publishing full-text reference works which are authoritative on various topics.
[src:infection/abc-clio] Libraries Unlimited came to ABC-Clio as part of a deal with Greenwood Press.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In 2012, Kathyrn Suárez was named publisher for this division, which focuses on publishing for librarians and information professionals.
[src:infection/abc-clio] ABC-Clio databases are provided under the umbrella of ABC-Clio Solutions.
[src:infection/abc-clio] There are fifteen different databases providing access to different subject areas.
[src:infection/abc-clio] ABC-Clio Solutions provides digital curriculum with multimedia content, text-to-speech features, translation tools which covers various topics relating to history and the humanities.
[src:infection/abc-clio] After ABC-Clio acquired Greenwood Press's databases, they revamped the look and feel of their interface in order to provide common access through the ABC-Clio interface.
[src:infection/abc-clio] ABC-Clio also provided the ability to search across multiple databases through one search, also providing options for narrowing the search after revamping their interface.
[src:infection/abc-clio] The new interface is considered user-friendly and provides access to personalized features.
[src:infection/abc-clio] Originally publishing books by disillusioned former Communists who had fled from behind the Iron Curtain, the publishing house became known for publishing "scholarly and professional books" in the subject areas of social sciences and the humanities.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In 1966, Praeger sold his firm to William B.
[src:infection/abc-clio] Benton, an American senator and publisher and the chairman of *Encyclopaedia Britannica*.
[src:infection/abc-clio] In 1976, it was sold to CBS, which had shortened the name to Praeger Publishing before selling it to Greenwood Press, Inc., in 1986.
[src:infection/abc-clio] When the renamed Greenwood Publishing Group (GPG) was acquired by ABC-Clio in 2009, Praeger Publishing became a standalone imprint of ABC-Clio, and remained such when, in December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing bought ABC-Clio.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The **human immunodeficiency virus** (HIV) is a retrovirus that attacks the immune system.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Without treatment, it can lead to a spectrum of conditions including **acquired immunodeficiency syndrome** (AIDS).
[src:infection/aids-p01] It can be managed with treatment and become a manageable chronic health condition.
[src:infection/aids-p01] While there is no cure or vaccine for HIV, antiretroviral treatment can slow the course of the disease, and, if used before significant disease progression, can extend the life expectancy of someone living with HIV to a nearly standard level.
[src:infection/aids-p01] An HIV-positive person on treatment can expect to live a normal life, and die with the virus, not of it.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Effective treatment for HIV-positive people (people living with HIV) involves a life-long regimen of medicine to suppress the virus, making the viral load undetectable.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Early testing can show if treatment is needed to stop progression and to prevent infecting others.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Treatment is recommended as soon as the diagnosis is made.
[src:infection/aids-p01] An HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Campaigns by UNAIDS and other organizations around the world have communicated this as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Without treatment the infection can interfere with the immune system, and eventually progress to AIDS, sometimes taking many years.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Following initial infection an individual may not notice any symptoms, or may experience a brief period of influenza-like illness.
[src:infection/aids-p01] During this period the person may not know that they are HIV-positive, yet they will be able to pass on the virus.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Typically, this period is followed by a prolonged incubation period with no symptoms.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Eventually the HIV infection increases the risk of developing other infections such as tuberculosis, as well as other opportunistic infections, and tumors which are rare in people who have normal immune function.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The late stage is often also associated with unintended weight loss.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Without treatment, the life expectancy of an individual with HIV is around 11 years.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV is spread primarily by unprotected sex (including anal, oral and vaginal sex), contaminated hypodermic needles or blood transfusions, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Some bodily fluids, such as saliva, sweat, and tears, do not transmit the virus.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Oral sex has little risk of transmitting the virus.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Ways to avoid catching HIV and preventing the spread include safe sex, treatment to prevent infection ("PrEP"), treatment to stop infection in someone who has been recently exposed ("PEP"), treating those who are infected, and needle exchange programs.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Disease in a baby can often be prevented by giving both the mother and child antiretroviral medication.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Recognized worldwide in the early 1980s, HIV/AIDS has had a large impact on society, both as an illness and as a source of discrimination.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The disease also has large economic impacts.
[src:infection/aids-p01] There are many misconceptions about HIV/AIDS, such as the belief that it can be transmitted by casual non-sexual contact.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The disease has become subject to many controversies involving religion, including the Catholic Church's position not to support condom use as prevention.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It has attracted international medical and political attention as well as large-scale funding since it was identified in the 1980s.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV made the jump from other primates to humans in west-central Africa in the early-to-mid-20th century.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 1981 and its cause—HIV infection—was identified in the early part of the decade.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Between the first time AIDS was readily identified through 2024, the disease is estimated to have caused at least 42.3 million deaths worldwide.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In 2025, 1.2 million people acquired HIV and an estimated 40.9 million people worldwide were living with HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a pandemic—a disease outbreak which is present over a large area and is actively spreading.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The United States' National Institutes of Health (NIH) and the Gates Foundation have pledged $200 million focused on developing a global cure for AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p01] There are three main stages of HIV infection: acute infection, clinical latency, and AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The initial period following infection with HIV is called acute HIV, primary HIV or acute retroviral syndrome.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Many individuals develop an influenza-like illness, mononucleosis or glandular fever 2–4 weeks after exposure while others have no significant symptoms.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Symptoms occur in 40–90% of cases and most commonly include fever, large tender lymph nodes, throat inflammation, a rash, headache, tiredness, and/or sores of the mouth and genitals.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The rash, which occurs in 20–50% of cases, presents itself on the trunk and is maculopapular, classically.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Some people also develop opportunistic infections at this stage.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Gastrointestinal symptoms, such as vomiting or diarrhea may occur.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Neurological symptoms of peripheral neuropathy or Guillain–Barré syndrome also occur.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The duration of the symptoms varies, but is usually one or two weeks.
[src:infection/aids-p01] These symptoms are not often recognized as signs of HIV infection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Family doctors or hospitals can misdiagnose cases as one of the many common infectious diseases with similar symptoms.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Someone with an unexplained fever who may have been recently exposed to HIV should consider testing to find out if they have been infected.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The initial symptoms are followed by a stage called clinical latency, asymptomatic HIV, or chronic HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Without treatment, this second stage of the natural history of HIV infection can last from about three years to over 20 years (on average, about eight years).
[src:infection/aids-p01] While typically there are few or no symptoms at first, near the end of this stage many people experience fever, weight loss, gastrointestinal problems and muscle pains.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Between 50% and 70% of people also develop persistent generalized lymphadenopathy, characterized by unexplained, non-painful enlargement of more than one group of lymph nodes (other than in the groin) for over three to six months.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Although most HIV-1 infected individuals have a detectable viral load and in the absence of treatment will eventually progress to AIDS, a small proportion (about 5%) retain high levels of CD4+ T cells (T helper cells) without antiretroviral therapy for more than five years.
[src:infection/aids-p01] These individuals are classified as "HIV controllers" or long-term nonprogressors (LTNP).
[src:infection/aids-p01] Another group consists of those who maintain a low or undetectable viral load without anti-retroviral treatment, known as "elite controllers" or "elite suppressors".
[src:infection/aids-p01] They represent approximately 1 in 300 infected persons.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) is defined as an HIV infection with either a CD4+ T cell count below 200 cells per microlitre (μL) of blood or the occurrence of specific diseases associated with HIV infection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In the absence of specific treatment, around half of people infected with HIV develop AIDS within ten years.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The most common initial conditions that alert to the presence of AIDS are pneumocystis pneumonia (40%), cachexia in the form of HIV wasting syndrome (20%), and esophageal candidiasis.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Other common signs include recurrent respiratory tract infections.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Opportunistic infections may be caused by bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites that are normally controlled by the immune system.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Which infections occur depends partly on what organisms are common in the person's environment.
[src:infection/aids-p01] These infections may affect nearly every organ system.
[src:infection/aids-p01] People with AIDS have an increased risk of developing various viral-induced cancers, including Kaposi's sarcoma, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Kaposi's sarcoma is the most common cancer, occurring in 10% to 20% of people with HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The second-most common cancer is lymphoma, which is the cause of death of nearly 16% of people with AIDS and is the initial sign of AIDS in 3% to 4%.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Both these cancers are associated with human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8).
[src:infection/aids-p01] Cervical cancer occurs more frequently in those with AIDS because of its association with human papillomavirus (HPV).
[src:infection/aids-p01] Conjunctival cancer (of the layer that lines the inner part of eyelids and the white part of the eye) is also more common in those with HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Additionally, people with AIDS frequently have systemic symptoms such as prolonged fevers, sweats (particularly at night), swollen lymph nodes, chills, weakness, and unintended weight loss.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Diarrhea is another common symptom, present in about 90% of people with AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p01] They can also be affected by diverse psychiatric and neurological symptoms independent of opportunistic infections and cancers.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV is spread by three main routes: sexual contact, significant exposure to infected body fluids or tissues, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding (known as vertical transmission).
[src:infection/aids-p01] There is no risk of acquiring HIV if exposed to feces, nasal secretions, saliva, sputum, sweat, tears, urine, or vomit unless these are contaminated with blood.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It is also possible to be co-infected by more than one strain of HIV—a condition known as HIV superinfection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The most frequent mode of transmission of HIV is through sexual contact with an infected person.
[src:infection/aids-p01] However, an HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually, known as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The existence of functionally noncontagious HIV-positive people on antiretroviral therapy was controversially publicized in the 2008 Swiss Statement, and has since become accepted as medically sound.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Globally, the most common mode of HIV transmission is via sexual contacts between people of the opposite sex; however, the pattern of transmission varies among countries.
[src:infection/aids-p01] As of 2017, most HIV transmission in the United States occurred among men who had sex with men (82% of new HIV diagnoses among males aged 13 and older and 70% of total new diagnoses).
[src:infection/aids-p01] In the US, gay and bisexual men aged 13 to 24 accounted for an estimated 92% of new HIV diagnoses among all men in their age group and 27% of new diagnoses among all gay and bisexual men.
[src:infection/aids-p01] With regard to unprotected heterosexual contacts, estimates of the risk of HIV transmission per sexual act appear to be four to ten times higher in low-income countries than in high-income countries.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The risk of transmission from anal intercourse is especially high, estimated as 1.4–1.7% per act in both heterosexual and homosexual contacts.
[src:infection/aids-p01] While the risk of transmission from oral sex is relatively low, it is still present.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The risk from receiving oral sex has been described as "nearly nil"; however, a few cases have been reported.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The per-act risk is estimated at 0–0.04% for receptive oral intercourse.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In settings involving prostitution in low-income countries, risk of female-to-male transmission has been estimated as 2.4% per act, and of male-to-female transmission as 0.05% per act.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Risk of transmission increases in the presence of many sexually transmitted infections and genital ulcers.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Genital ulcers increase the risk approximately fivefold.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Other sexually transmitted infections, such as gonorrhea, chlamydia, trichomoniasis, and bacterial vaginosis, are associated with somewhat smaller increases in risk of transmission.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The viral load of an infected person is an important risk factor in both sexual and mother-to-child transmission.
[src:infection/aids-p01] During the first 2.5 months of an HIV infection, a person's infectiousness is twelve times higher due to the high viral load associated with acute HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] If the person is in the late stages of infection, rates of transmission are approximately eightfold greater.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Commercial sex workers (including those in pornography) have an increased likelihood of contracting HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Rough sex can be a factor associated with an increased risk of transmission.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Sexual assault is also believed to carry an increased risk of HIV transmission, as condoms are rarely worn, physical trauma to the vagina or rectum is likely, and there may be a greater risk of concurrent sexually transmitted infections.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The second-most frequent mode of HIV transmission is via blood and blood products.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Blood-borne transmission can be through needle-sharing during intravenous drug use, needle-stick injury, transfusion of contaminated blood or blood product, or medical injections with unsterilized equipment.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The risk from sharing a needle during drug injection is between 0.63% and 2.4% per act, with an average of 0.8%.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The risk of acquiring HIV from a needle stick from an HIV-infected person is estimated as 0.3% (about 1 in 333) per act and the risk following mucous membrane exposure to infected blood as 0.09% (about 1 in 1000) per act.
[src:infection/aids-p01] This risk may, however, be up to 5% if the introduced blood was from a person with a high viral load and the cut was deep.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In the United States, intravenous drug users made up 12% of all new cases of HIV in 2009, and in some areas more than 80% of people who inject drugs are predicted to be HIV-positive.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV is transmitted in about 90% of blood transfusions using infected blood.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In low-income countries, only half of transfusions may be appropriately screened (as of 2008), and it is estimated that up to 15% of HIV infections in these areas come from transfusion of infected blood and blood products, representing between 5% and 10% of global infections.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It is possible to acquire HIV from organ and tissue transplantation, although this is rare because of screening.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Unsafe medical injections play a role in HIV spread in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In 2007, between 12% and 17% of infections in this region were attributed to medical syringe use.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The World Health Organization estimates the risk of transmission as a result of a medical injection in Africa at 1.2%.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Risks are also associated with invasive procedures, assisted delivery, and dental care in this area of the world.
[src:infection/aids-p01] People giving or receiving tattoos, piercings, and scarification are theoretically at risk of infection but no confirmed cases have been documented.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It is not possible for mosquitoes or other insects to transmit HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV can be transmitted from mother to child during pregnancy, during delivery, or through breast milk, resulting in the baby also contracting HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] As of 2008, vertical transmission accounted for about 90% of cases of HIV in children.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In the absence of treatment, the risk of transmission before or during birth is around 20%, and in those who also breastfeed 35%.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Treatment decreases this risk to less than 5%.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Antiretrovirals when taken by either the mother or the baby decrease the risk of transmission in those who do breastfeed.
[src:infection/aids-p01] If blood contaminates food during pre-chewing it may pose a risk of transmission.
[src:infection/aids-p01] If a woman is untreated, two years of breastfeeding results in an HIV/AIDS risk in her baby of about 17%.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Due to the increased risk of death without breastfeeding in many areas in the developing world, the World Health Organization recommends either exclusive breastfeeding or the provision of safe formula.
[src:infection/aids-p01] All women known to be HIV-positive should be taking lifelong antiretroviral therapy.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV is the cause of the spectrum of disease known as HIV/AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV is a retrovirus that primarily infects components of the human immune system such as CD4+ T cells, macrophages and dendritic cells.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It directly and indirectly destroys CD4+ T cells.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV is a member of the genus *Lentivirus*, part of the family *Retroviridae*.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Lentiviruses share many morphological and biological characteristics.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Many species of mammals are infected by lentiviruses, which are characteristically responsible for long-duration illnesses with a long incubation period.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Lentiviruses are transmitted as single-stranded, positive-sense, enveloped RNA viruses.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Upon entry into the target cell, the viral RNA genome is converted (reverse transcribed) into double-stranded DNA by a virally encoded reverse transcriptase that is transported along with the viral genome in the virus particle.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The resulting viral DNA is then imported into the cell nucleus and integrated into the cellular DNA by a virally encoded integrase and host co-factors.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Once integrated, the virus may become latent, allowing the virus and its host cell to avoid detection by the immune system.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Alternatively, the virus may be transcribed, producing new RNA genomes and viral proteins that are packaged and released from the cell as new virus particles that begin the replication cycle anew.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV is now known to spread between CD4+ T cells by two parallel routes: cell-free spread and cell-to-cell spread, i.e. it employs hybrid spreading mechanisms.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In the cell-free spread, virus particles bud from an infected T cell, enter the blood/extracellular fluid and then infect another T cell following a chance encounter.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV can also disseminate by direct transmission from one cell to another by a process of cell-to-cell spread.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The hybrid spreading mechanisms of HIV contribute to the virus' ongoing replication against antiretroviral therapies.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Two types of HIV have been characterized: HIV-1 and HIV-2.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV-1 is the virus that was originally discovered (and initially referred to also as LAV or HTLV-III).
[src:infection/aids-p01] It is more virulent, more infective, and is the cause of the majority of HIV infections globally.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The lower infectivity of HIV-2 as compared with HIV-1 implies that fewer people exposed to HIV-2 will be infected per exposure.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Because of its relatively poor capacity for transmission, HIV-2 is largely confined to West Africa.
[src:infection/aids-p01] After the virus enters the body, there is a period of rapid viral replication, leading to an abundance of virus in the peripheral blood.
[src:infection/aids-p01] During primary infection, the level of HIV may reach several million virus particles per milliliter of blood.
[src:infection/aids-p01] This response is accompanied by a marked drop in the number of circulating CD4+ T cells.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The acute viremia is almost invariably associated with activation of CD8+ T cells, which kill HIV-infected cells, and subsequently with antibody production, or seroconversion.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The CD8+ T cell response is thought to be important in controlling virus levels, which peak and then decline, as the CD4+ T cell counts recover.
[src:infection/aids-p01] A good CD8+ T cell response has been linked to slower disease progression and a better prognosis, though it does not eliminate the virus.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Ultimately, HIV causes AIDS by depleting CD4+ T cells.
[src:infection/aids-p01] This weakens the immune system and allows opportunistic infections.
[src:infection/aids-p01] T cells are essential to the immune response and without them, the body cannot fight infections or kill cancerous cells.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The mechanism of CD4+ T cell depletion differs in the acute and chronic phases.
[src:infection/aids-p01] During the acute phase, HIV-induced cell lysis and killing of infected cells by CD8+ T cells accounts for CD4+ T cell depletion, although apoptosis may also be a factor.
[src:infection/aids-p01] During the chronic phase, the consequences of generalized immune activation coupled with the gradual loss of the ability of the immune system to generate new T cells appear to account for the slow decline in CD4+ T cell numbers.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Although the symptoms of immune deficiency characteristic of AIDS do not appear for years after a person is infected, the bulk of CD4+ T cell loss occurs during the first weeks of infection, especially in the intestinal mucosa, which harbors the majority of the lymphocytes found in the body.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The reason for the preferential loss of mucosal CD4+ T cells is that the majority of mucosal CD4+ T cells express the CCR5 protein which HIV uses as a co-receptor to gain access to the cells, whereas only a small fraction of CD4+ T cells in the bloodstream do so.
[src:infection/aids-p01] A specific genetic change that alters the CCR5 protein when present in both chromosomes very effectively prevents HIV-1 infection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV seeks out and destroys CCR5 expressing CD4+ T cells during acute infection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] A vigorous immune response eventually controls the infection and initiates the clinically latent phase.
[src:infection/aids-p01] CD4+ T cells in mucosal tissues remain particularly affected.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Continuous HIV replication causes a state of generalized immune activation persisting throughout the chronic phase.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Immune activation, which is reflected by the increased activation state of immune cells and release of pro-inflammatory cytokines, results from the activity of several HIV gene products and the immune response to ongoing HIV replication.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It is also linked to the breakdown of the immune surveillance system of the gastrointestinal mucosal barrier caused by the depletion of mucosal CD4+ T cells during the acute phase of disease.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS related eye diseases are common among people living with this disease worldwide.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Among these diseases, HIV retinopathy is the most common condition.
[src:infection/aids-p01] This condition is seen in 40% to 60% of HIV positive patients.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It is also the most common cause of loss of vision in these patients.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is diagnosed via laboratory testing and then staged based on the presence of certain signs or symptoms.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV screening is recommended by the United States Preventive Services Task Force for all people 15 years to 65 years of age, including all pregnant women.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Additionally, testing is recommended for those at high risk, which includes anyone diagnosed with a sexually transmitted illness.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In many areas of the world, a third of HIV carriers only discover they are infected at an advanced stage of the disease when AIDS or severe immunodeficiency has become apparent.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Most people infected with HIV develop seroconverted (antigen-specific) antibodies within three to twelve weeks after the initial infection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Diagnosis of primary HIV before seroconversion is done by measuring HIV-RNA or p24 antigen.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Positive results obtained by antibody or PCR testing are confirmed either by a different antibody or by PCR.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Antibody tests in children younger than 18 months are typically inaccurate, due to the continued presence of maternal antibodies.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Thus HIV infection can only be diagnosed by PCR testing for HIV RNA or DNA, or via testing for the p24 antigen.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Much of the world lacks access to reliable PCR testing, and people in many places simply wait until either symptoms develop or the child is old enough for accurate antibody testing.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In sub-Saharan Africa between 2007 and 2009, between 30% and 70% of the population were aware of their HIV status.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In 2009, between 3.6% and 42% of men and women in sub-Saharan countries were tested; this represented a significant increase compared to previous years.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Two main clinical staging systems are used to classify HIV and HIV-related disease for surveillance purposes: the WHO disease staging system for HIV infection and disease, and the CDC classification system for HIV infection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The CDC's classification system is more frequently adopted in developed countries.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Since the WHO's staging system does not require laboratory tests, it is suited to the resource-restricted conditions encountered in developing countries, where it can also be used to help guide clinical management.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Despite their differences, the two systems allow a comparison for statistical purposes.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The World Health Organization first proposed a definition for AIDS in 1986.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Since then, the WHO classification has been updated and expanded several times, with the most recent version being published in 2007.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also created a classification system for HIV, and updated it in 2008 and 2014.
[src:infection/aids-p01] This system classifies HIV infections based on CD4 count and clinical symptoms, and describes the infection in five groups.
[src:infection/aids-p01] For surveillance purposes, the AIDS diagnosis still stands even if, after treatment, the CD4+ T cell count rises to above 200 per μL of blood or other AIDS-defining illnesses are cured.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Consistent condom use reduces the risk of HIV transmission by approximately 80% over the long term.
[src:infection/aids-p01] When condoms are used consistently by a couple in which one person is infected, the rate of HIV infection is less than 1% per year.
[src:infection/aids-p01] There is some evidence to suggest that female condoms may provide an equivalent level of protection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Application of a vaginal gel containing tenofovir (a reverse transcriptase inhibitor) immediately before sex seems to reduce infection rates by approximately 40% among African women.
[src:infection/aids-p01] By contrast, use of the spermicide nonoxynol-9 may increase the risk of transmission due to its tendency to cause vaginal and rectal irritation.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Circumcision in sub-Saharan Africa "reduces the acquisition of HIV by heterosexual men by between 38% and 66% over 24 months".
[src:infection/aids-p01] Owing to these studies, both the World Health Organization and UNAIDS recommended male circumcision in 2007 as a method of preventing female-to-male HIV transmission in areas with high rates of HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] However, whether it protects against male-to-female transmission is disputed, and whether it is of benefit in developed countries and among men who have sex with men is undetermined.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Programs encouraging sexual abstinence do not appear to affect subsequent HIV risk.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Evidence of any benefit from peer education is equally poor.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Comprehensive sexual education provided at school may decrease high-risk behavior.
[src:infection/aids-p01] A substantial minority of young people continues to engage in high-risk practices despite knowing about HIV/AIDS, underestimating their own risk of becoming infected with HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Voluntary counseling and testing people for HIV does not affect risky behavior in those who test negative but does increase condom use in those who test positive.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Enhanced family planning services appear to increase the likelihood of women with HIV using contraception, compared to basic services.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It is not known whether treating other sexually transmitted infections is effective in preventing HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Antiretroviral treatment among people with HIV whose CD4 count ≤ 550 cells/μL is a very effective way to prevent HIV infection of their partner (a strategy known as treatment as prevention, or TASP).
[src:infection/aids-p01] TASP is associated with a 10- to 20-fold reduction in transmission risk.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Pre-exposure prophylaxis for HIV ("PrEP") with a daily dose of the medications tenofovir, with or without emtricitabine, is effective in people at high risk including men who have sex with men, couples where one is HIV-positive, and young heterosexuals in Africa.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It may also be effective in intravenous drug users, with a study finding a decrease in risk of 0.7 to 0.4 per 100 person years.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The USPSTF, in 2019, recommended PrEP in those who are at high risk.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Universal precautions within the health care environment are believed to be effective in decreasing the risk of HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Intravenous drug use is an important risk factor, and harm reduction strategies such as needle-exchange programs and opioid substitution therapy appear effective in decreasing this risk.
[src:infection/aids-p01] A course of antiretrovirals administered within 48 to 72 hours after exposure to HIV-positive blood or genital secretions is referred to as post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP).
[src:infection/aids-p01] The use of the single agent zidovudine reduces the risk of an HIV infection five-fold following a needle-stick injury.
[src:infection/aids-p01] As of 2013, the prevention regimen recommended in the United States consists of three medications—tenofovir, emtricitabine and raltegravir—as this may reduce the risk further.
[src:infection/aids-p01] PEP treatment is recommended after a sexual assault when the perpetrator is known to be HIV-positive, but is controversial when their HIV status is unknown.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The duration of treatment is usually four weeks and is frequently associated with adverse effects—where zidovudine is used, about 70% of cases result in adverse effects such as nausea (24%), fatigue (22%), emotional distress (13%) and headaches (9%).
[src:infection/aids-p01] Programs to prevent the vertical transmission of HIV (from mothers to children) can reduce rates of transmission by 92–99%.
[src:infection/aids-p01] This primarily involves the use of a combination of antiviral medications during pregnancy and after birth in the infant, and potentially includes bottle feeding rather than breastfeeding.
[src:infection/aids-p01] If replacement feeding is acceptable, feasible, affordable, sustainable and safe, mothers should avoid breastfeeding their infants; however, exclusive breastfeeding is recommended during the first months of life if this is not the case.
[src:infection/aids-p01] If exclusive breastfeeding is carried out, the provision of extended antiretroviral prophylaxis to the infant decreases the risk of transmission.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In 2015, Cuba became the first country in the world to eradicate mother-to-child transmission of HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Currently there is no licensed vaccine for HIV or AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The most effective vaccine trial to date, RV 144, was published in 2009; it found a partial reduction in the risk of transmission of roughly 30%, stimulating some hope in the research community of developing a truly effective vaccine.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is a chronic condition, as there is currently no cure.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Treatment consists of highly active antiretroviral therapy (ART), which slows progression of the disease.
[src:infection/aids-p01] As of 2025, 40.9 million people globally were living with HIV, and 32.1 million people were accessing ART.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Treatment also includes preventive and active treatment of opportunistic infections.
[src:infection/aids-p01] As of July 2022, four people have been successfully cleared of HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Rapid initiation of antiretroviral therapy within one week of diagnosis appear to improve treatment outcomes in low and medium-income settings and is recommend for newly diagnosed HIV patients.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV retinopathy was a very common cause of blindness in people with AIDS before the introduction of highly active antiretroviral therapy, but its incidence is declining due to proper and timely management of AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Even if there are signs of retinopathy, it may reverse as CD4+ T cell counts increase.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Reversal of HIV retinopathy is a helpful sign of positive response to antiretroviral therapy in AIDS patients.
[src:infection/aids-p01] But if HIV treatment is delayed it may lead to permanent visual loss.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Occurrence of HIV retinopathy may also be an indicator of therapeutic failure in AIDS patients undergoing treatment.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Current ART options are combinations (or "cocktails") consisting of at least three medications belonging to at least two types, or "classes", of antiretroviral agents.
[src:infection/aids-p01] There are also two drugs, ritonavir (RTV) and cobicistat (COBI) which can be used as pharmacokinetic (PK) enhancers (or boosters) to improve the PK profiles of PIs and the INSTI elvitegravir (EVG).
[src:infection/aids-p01] The World Health Organization and the United States recommend antiretrovirals in people of all ages (including pregnant women) as soon as the diagnosis is made, regardless of CD4 count.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Once treatment is begun, it is recommended that it is continued without breaks or "holidays".
[src:infection/aids-p01] Many people are diagnosed only after treatment ideally should have begun.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The desired outcome of treatment is a long-term plasma HIV-RNA count below 50 copies/mL.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Levels to determine if treatment is effective are initially recommended after four weeks and once levels fall below 50 copies/mL checks every three to six months are typically adequate.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Inadequate control is deemed to be greater than 400 copies/mL.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Based on these criteria treatment is effective in more than 95% of people during the first year.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Benefits of treatment include a decreased risk of progression to AIDS and a decreased risk of death.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In the developing world, treatment also improves physical and mental health.
[src:infection/aids-p01] With treatment, there is a 70% reduced risk of acquiring tuberculosis.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Additional benefits include a decreased risk of transmission of the disease to sexual partners and a decrease in mother-to-child transmission.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The effectiveness of treatment depends to a large part on compliance.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Reasons for non-adherence to treatment include poor access to medical care, inadequate social supports, mental illness and drug abuse.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The complexity of treatment regimens (due to pill numbers and dosing frequency) and adverse effects may reduce adherence.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Even though cost is an important issue with some medications, 47% of those who needed them were taking them in low- and middle-income countries as of 2010, and the rate of adherence is similar in low-income and high-income countries.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Specific adverse events are related to the antiretroviral agent taken.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Some relatively common adverse events include: lipodystrophy syndrome, dyslipidemia, and diabetes mellitus, especially with protease inhibitors.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Other common symptoms include diarrhea, and an increased risk of cardiovascular disease.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Newer recommended treatments are associated with fewer adverse effects.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Certain medications may be associated with birth defects and therefore may be unsuitable for women hoping to have children.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Treatment recommendations for children are somewhat different from those for adults.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The World Health Organization recommends treating all children less than five years of age; children above five are treated like adults.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The United States guidelines recommend treating all children less than 12 months of age and all those with HIV RNA counts greater than 100,000 copies/mL between one year and five years of age.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In 2020, the European Medicines Agency recommended approval of a long-acting injectable combination of the antiretrovirals rilpivirine and cabotegravir, marketed as Rekambys and Vocabria; unlike standard daily pills, it is administered by intramuscular injection every one to two months.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It is indicated as maintenance therapy for adults who are already virologically suppressed (viral load below 50 copies/mL) on a stable regimen, with no documented resistance to non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors or integrase strand transfer inhibitors.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Measures to prevent opportunistic infections are effective in many people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In addition to improving current disease, treatment with antiretrovirals reduces the risk of developing additional opportunistic infections.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Adults and adolescents who are living with HIV (even on anti-retroviral therapy) with no evidence of active tuberculosis in settings with high tuberculosis burden should receive isoniazid preventive therapy (IPT); the tuberculin skin test can be used to help decide if IPT is needed.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Children with HIV may benefit from screening for tuberculosis.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Vaccination against hepatitis A and B is advised for all people at risk of HIV before they become infected; however, it may also be given after infection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole prophylaxis between four and six weeks of age, and ceasing breastfeeding of infants born to HIV-positive mothers, is recommended in resource-limited settings.
[src:infection/aids-p01] It is also recommended to prevent PCP when a person's CD4 count is below 200 cells/uL and in those who have or have previously had PCP.
[src:infection/aids-p01] People with substantial immunosuppression are also advised to receive prophylactic therapy for toxoplasmosis and MAC.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Appropriate preventive measures reduced the rate of these infections by 50% between 1992 and 1997.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Influenza vaccination and pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine are often recommended in people with HIV/AIDS with some evidence of benefit.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) has issued recommendations regarding nutrient requirements in HIV/AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Dietary intake of micronutrients at RDA levels by HIV-infected adults is recommended by the WHO; higher intake of vitamin A, zinc, and iron can produce adverse effects in HIV-positive adults, and is not recommended unless there is documented deficiency.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Dietary supplementation for people who are infected with HIV and who have inadequate nutrition or dietary deficiencies may strengthen their immune systems or help them recover from infections; however, evidence indicating an overall benefit in morbidity or reduction in mortality is not consistent.
[src:infection/aids-p01] People with HIV/AIDS are up to four times more likely to develop type 2 diabetes than those who are not tested positive with the virus.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Evidence for supplementation with selenium is mixed with some tentative evidence of benefit.
[src:infection/aids-p01] For pregnant and lactating women with HIV, multivitamin supplement improves outcomes for both mothers and children.
[src:infection/aids-p01] If the pregnant or lactating mother has been advised to take anti-retroviral medication to prevent mother-to-child HIV transmission, multivitamin supplements should not replace these treatments.
[src:infection/aids-p01] There is some evidence that vitamin A supplementation in children with an HIV infection reduces mortality and improves growth.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In the US, approximately 60% of people with HIV use various forms of complementary or alternative medicine, whose effectiveness has not been established.
[src:infection/aids-p01] There is not enough evidence to support the use of herbal medicines.
[src:infection/aids-p01] There is insufficient evidence to recommend or support the use of medical cannabis to try to increase appetite or weight gain.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS has become a chronic rather than an acutely fatal disease in many areas of the world.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Prognosis varies between people, and both the CD4 count and viral load are useful for predicted outcomes.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Without treatment, average survival time after infection with HIV is estimated to be 9 to 11 years, depending on the HIV subtype.
[src:infection/aids-p01] After the diagnosis of AIDS, if treatment is not available, survival ranges between 6 and 19 months.
[src:infection/aids-p01] ART and appropriate prevention of opportunistic infections reduces the death rate by 80%, and raises the life expectancy for a newly diagnosed young adult to 20–50 years.
[src:infection/aids-p01] This is between two thirds and nearly that of the general population.
[src:infection/aids-p01] If treatment is started late in the infection, prognosis is not as good: for example, if treatment is begun following the diagnosis of AIDS, life expectancy is ~10–40 years.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Half of infants born with HIV die before two years of age without treatment.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The primary causes of death from HIV/AIDS are opportunistic infections and cancer, both of which are frequently the result of the progressive failure of the immune system.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Risk of cancer appears to increase once the CD4 count is below 500/μL.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Tuberculosis co-infection is one of the leading causes of sickness and death in those with HIV/AIDS being present in a third of all HIV-infected people and causing 25% of HIV-related deaths.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV is also one of the most important risk factors for tuberculosis.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Hepatitis C is another very common co-infection where each disease increases the progression of the other.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The two most common cancers associated with HIV/AIDS are Kaposi's sarcoma and AIDS-related non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Other cancers that are more frequent include anal cancer, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Even with anti-retroviral treatment, over the long term HIV-infected people may experience neurocognitive disorders, osteoporosis, neuropathy, cancers, nephropathy, and cardiovascular disease.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Some conditions, such as lipodystrophy, may be caused both by HIV and its treatment.
[src:infection/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a global pandemic.
[src:infection/aids-p01] As of 2025, approximately 40.9 million people worldwide are living with HIV, the number of new infections that year being about 1.2 million.
[src:infection/aids-p01] This is down 43% from 2.1 million new infections in 2010.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Among new infections, 41% are in women and girls globally.
[src:infection/aids-p01] There were [CONFIRM 2025 figure] AIDS-related deaths in 2025, down from a peak of 2 million in 2005.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Among persons living with HIV (PLWH), the largest proportion reside in eastern and southern Africa (20.6 million, 54.6%).
[src:infection/aids-p01] This region also had the highest rate of adult and child deaths due to AIDS in 2020 (310,000, 46.6%).
[src:infection/aids-p01] Sub-Saharan African adolescent girls and young women (aged 15–24 years) account for 77% of new infections among this age-range globally.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Here, in contrast to other regions, adolescent girls and young women are three times more likely to acquire HIV than age-matched males.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Despite these statistics, overall, new HIV infections and AIDS-related deaths have substantially decreased in this region since 2010.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Eastern Europe and central Asia has observed a 43% increase in new HIV infections and 32% increase in AIDS-related deaths since 2010, the highest of all global regions.
[src:infection/aids-p01] These infections are predominantly distributed in persons who inject drugs, with gay men and other men who have sex with men or persons who engage in transaction sex the second and third populations most impacted in this region.
[src:infection/aids-p01] At the end of 2019, United States indicated that approximately 1.2 million people aged ≥13 years were living with HIV, resulting in about 18,500 deaths in 2020.
[src:infection/aids-p01] There were 34,800 estimated new infections in the US in 2019, 53% of which were in the southern region of the country.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In addition to geographic location, significant disparities in HIV incidence exist among men, Black or Hispanic populations, and men who reported male-to-male sexual contact.
[src:infection/aids-p01] The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimated that in that year, 158,500 people or 13% of infected Americans were unaware of their infection.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In the United Kingdom as of 2015, there were approximately 101,200 cases which resulted in 594 deaths.
[src:infection/aids-p01] In Canada as of 2008, there were about 65,000 cases causing 53 deaths.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Between the first recognition of AIDS (in 1981) and 2009, it has led to nearly 30 million deaths.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Rates of HIV are lowest in North Africa and the Middle East (0.1% or less), East Asia (0.1%), and Western and Central Europe (0.2%).
[src:infection/aids-p01] The worst-affected European countries, in 2009 and 2012 estimates, are Russia, Ukraine, Latvia, Moldova, Portugal and Belarus, in decreasing order of prevalence.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Groups at higher risk of acquiring HIV include persons who engage in transactional sex, gay men and other men who have sex with men, persons who inject drugs, transgender persons, and those who are incarcerated or detained.
[src:infection/aids-p01] Climate change impacts HIV risk and the availability of and access to HIV prevention and treatment services, and can contribute to poor nutrition, impaired immunity, and poor adherence to treatment.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The first news story on the disease appeared on May 18, 1981, in the gay newspaper *New York Native*.
[src:infection/aids-p02] AIDS was first clinically reported on June 5, 1981, with five cases in the United States.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The initial cases were a cluster of injecting drug users and gay men with no known cause of impaired immunity who showed symptoms of *Pneumocystis carinii* pneumonia (PCP), a rare opportunistic infection that was known to occur in people with very compromised immune systems.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Soon thereafter, a large number of homosexual men developed a generally rare skin cancer called Kaposi's sarcoma (KS).
[src:infection/aids-p02] Many more cases of PCP and KS emerged, alerting the U.S.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and a CDC task force was formed to monitor the outbreak.
[src:infection/aids-p02] In the early days, the CDC did not have an official name for the disease, often referring to it by way of diseases associated with it, such as lymphadenopathy, the disease after which the discoverers of HIV originally named the virus.
[src:infection/aids-p02] They also used *Kaposi's sarcoma and opportunistic infections*, the name by which a task force had been set up in 1981.
[src:infection/aids-p02] At one point the CDC referred to it as the "4H disease", as the syndrome seemed to affect heroin users, homosexuals, hemophiliacs, and Haitians.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The term *GRID*, which stood for gay-related immune deficiency, had also been coined.
[src:infection/aids-p02] However, after determining that AIDS was not isolated to the gay community, it was realized that the term *GRID* was misleading, and the term *AIDS* was introduced at a meeting in July 1982.
[src:infection/aids-p02] By September 1982 the CDC started referring to the disease as AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p02] In 1983, two separate research groups led by Robert Gallo and Luc Montagnier declared that a novel retrovirus may have been infecting people with AIDS, and published their findings in the same issue of the journal *Science*.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Gallo claimed a virus which his group had isolated from a person with AIDS was strikingly similar in shape to other human T-lymphotropic viruses (HTLVs) that his group had been the first to isolate.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Gallo's group called their newly isolated virus HTLV-III.
[src:infection/aids-p02] At the same time, Montagnier's group isolated a virus from a person presenting with swelling of the lymph nodes of the neck and physical weakness, two characteristic symptoms of AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Contradicting the report from Gallo's group, Montagnier and his colleagues showed that core proteins of this virus were immunologically different from those of HTLV-I.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Montagnier's group named their isolated virus lymphadenopathy-associated virus (LAV).
[src:infection/aids-p02] As these two viruses turned out to be the same, in 1986, LAV and HTLV-III were renamed HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The origin of HIV / AIDS and the circumstances that led to its emergence remain unsolved.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Both HIV-1 and HIV-2 are believed to have originated in non-human primates in West-central Africa and were transferred to humans in the early 20th century.
[src:infection/aids-p02] HIV-1 appears to have originated in southern Cameroon through the evolution of SIV(cpz), a simian immunodeficiency virus (SIV) that infects wild chimpanzees (HIV-1 descends from the SIVcpz endemic in the chimpanzee subspecies *Pan troglodytes troglodytes*).
[src:infection/aids-p02] The closest relative of HIV-2 is SIV (smm), a virus of the sooty mangabey (*Cercocebus atys atys*), an Old World monkey living in coastal West Africa (from southern Senegal to western Ivory Coast).
[src:infection/aids-p02] New World monkeys such as the owl monkey are resistant to HIV-1 infection, possibly because of a genomic fusion of two viral resistance genes.
[src:infection/aids-p02] HIV-1 is thought to have jumped the species barrier on at least three separate occasions, giving rise to the three groups of the virus, M, N, and O.
[src:infection/aids-p02] There is evidence that humans who participate in bushmeat activities, either as hunters or as bushmeat vendors, commonly acquire SIV.
[src:infection/aids-p02] However, SIV is a weak virus which is typically suppressed by the human immune system within weeks of infection.
[src:infection/aids-p02] It is thought that several transmissions of the virus from individual to individual in quick succession are necessary to allow it enough time to mutate into HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Furthermore, due to its relatively low person-to-person transmission rate, SIV can only spread throughout the population in the presence of one or more high-risk transmission channels, which are thought to have been absent in Africa before the 20th century.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Specific proposed high-risk transmission channels, allowing the virus to adapt to humans and spread throughout society, depend on the proposed timing of the animal-to-human crossing.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Genetic studies of the virus suggest that the most recent common ancestor of the HIV-1 M group dates back to c.
[src:infection/aids-p02] While transmission rates of HIV during vaginal intercourse are low under regular circumstances, they are increased manyfold if one of the partners has a sexually transmitted infection causing genital ulcers.
[src:infection/aids-p02] An alternative view holds that unsafe medical practices in Africa after World War II, such as unsterile reuse of single-use syringes during mass vaccination, antibiotic and anti-malaria treatment campaigns, were the initial vector that allowed the virus to adapt to humans and spread.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The earliest well-documented case of HIV in a human dates back to 1959 in the Congo.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The virus may have been present in the U.S. as early as the mid-to-late 1950s.
[src:infection/aids-p02] A 16-year-old male named Robert Rayford presented with symptoms in 1966 and died in 1969.
[src:infection/aids-p02] In the 1970s, there were cases of people getting parasites and becoming sick with what was then called "gay bowel disease" but is now suspected to have been AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The earliest retrospectively described case of AIDS is believed to have been in Norway beginning in 1966, that of Arvid Noe.
[src:infection/aids-p02] In July 1960, in the wake of Congo's independence, the United Nations recruited Francophone experts and technicians from all over the world to assist in filling administrative gaps left by Belgium, who did not leave behind an African elite to run the country.
[src:infection/aids-p02] By 1962, Haitians made up the second-largest group of well-educated experts (out of the 48 national groups recruited), that totaled around 4,500 in the country.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Jacques Pépin, a Canadian author of *The Origins of AIDS*, stipulates that Haiti was one of HIV's entry points to the U.S. and that a Haitian may have carried HIV back across the Atlantic in the 1960s.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The epidemic rapidly spread among high-risk groups (initially, sexually promiscuous men who have sex with men).
[src:infection/aids-p02] By 1978, the prevalence of HIV-1 among gay male residents of New York City and San Francisco was estimated at 5%, suggesting that several thousand individuals in the country had been infected.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Stigma-related violence or the fear of violence prevents many people from seeking HIV testing, returning for their results, or securing treatment, possibly turning what could be a manageable chronic illness into a death sentence and perpetuating the spread of HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Often, AIDS stigma is expressed in conjunction with one or more other stigmas, particularly those associated with homosexuality, bisexuality, promiscuity, prostitution, and intravenous drug use.
[src:infection/aids-p02] In many developed countries, there is an association between AIDS and homosexuality or bisexuality, and this association is correlated with higher levels of sexual prejudice, such as anti-homosexual or anti-bisexual attitudes.
[src:infection/aids-p02] There is also a perceived association between AIDS and all male-male sexual behavior, including sex between uninfected men.
[src:infection/aids-p02] However, the dominant mode of spread worldwide for HIV remains heterosexual transmission.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The NAMES Project AIDS Memorial Quilt was conceived in 1985 to celebrate the lives of those who had died of AIDS when stigma prevented many from receiving funerals.
[src:infection/aids-p02] It is now cared for by the National AIDS Memorial in San Francisco.
[src:infection/aids-p02] In 2003, as part of an overall reform of marriage and population legislation, it became legal for those diagnosed with AIDS to marry in China.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Between 2004 and 2020, Somen Debnath has travelled the world by bicycle promoting HIV / AIDS awareness.
[src:infection/aids-p02] National Library of Medicine developed a traveling exhibition titled *Surviving and Thriving: AIDS, Politics, and Culture*; this covered medical research, the U.S. government's response, and personal stories from people with AIDS, caregivers, and activists.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Stigma has proved an obstacle to the update of PrEP.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Within the MSM community, the greatest barrier to PrEP use has been the stigma surrounding HIV and gay men.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Gay men on PrEP have experienced "slut-shaming".
[src:infection/aids-p02] Numerous other barriers have been identified, including lack of quality LGBTQ care, cost, and adherence to medication use.
[src:infection/aids-p02] HIV/AIDS affects the economics of both individuals and countries.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The gross domestic product of the most affected countries has decreased due to the lack of human capital.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Without proper nutrition, health care and medicine, large numbers of people die from AIDS-related complications.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Before death they will not only be unable to work, but will also require significant medical care.
[src:infection/aids-p02] It is estimated that as of 2007 there were 12 million AIDS orphans.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Many are cared for by elderly grandparents.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Returning to work after beginning treatment for HIV/AIDS is difficult, and affected people often work less than the average worker.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Unemployment in people with HIV/AIDS also is associated with suicidal ideation, memory problems, and social isolation.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Employment increases self-esteem, sense of dignity, confidence, and quality of life for people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Anti-retroviral treatment may help people with HIV/AIDS work more, and may increase the chance that a person with HIV/AIDS will be employed (low-quality evidence).
[src:infection/aids-p02] By affecting mainly young adults, AIDS reduces the taxable population, in turn reducing the resources available for public expenditures such as education and health services not related to AIDS, resulting in increasing pressure on the state's finances and slower growth of the economy.
[src:infection/aids-p02] This causes a slower growth of the tax base, an effect that is reinforced if there are growing expenditures on treating the sick, training (to replace sick workers), sick pay, and caring for AIDS orphans.
[src:infection/aids-p02] This is especially true if the sharp increase in adult mortality shifts the responsibility from the family to the government in caring for these orphans.
[src:infection/aids-p02] At the household level, AIDS causes both loss of income and increased spending on healthcare.
[src:infection/aids-p02] A study in Côte d'Ivoire showed that households having a person with HIV/AIDS spent twice as much on medical expenses as other households.
[src:infection/aids-p02] This additional expenditure also leaves less income to spend on education and other personal or family investment.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The topic of religion and AIDS has become highly controversial, primarily because some religious authorities have publicly declared their opposition to the use of condoms.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Some religious organizations have claimed that prayer can cure HIV/AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p02] In 2011, the BBC reported that some churches in London were claiming that prayer would cure AIDS, and the Hackney-based Centre for the Study of Sexual Health and HIV reported that several people stopped taking their medication, sometimes on the direct advice of their pastor, leading to many deaths.
[src:infection/aids-p02] The Synagogue Church Of All Nations advertised an "anointing water" to promote God's healing, although the group denies advising people to stop taking medication.
[src:infection/aids-p02] One of the first high-profile cases of AIDS was the American gay actor Rock Hudson.
[src:infection/aids-p02] He had been diagnosed during 1984, announced that he had had the virus on July 25, 1985, and died a few months later on October 2, 1985.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Another notable British casualty of AIDS that year was Nicholas Eden, a gay politician and son of former prime minister Anthony Eden.
[src:infection/aids-p02] On November 24, 1991, British rock star Freddie Mercury died from an AIDS-related illness, having revealed the diagnosis only on the previous day.
[src:infection/aids-p02] One of the first high-profile heterosexual cases of the virus was American tennis player Arthur Ashe.
[src:infection/aids-p02] He was diagnosed as HIV-positive on August 31, 1988, having contracted the virus from blood transfusions during heart surgery earlier in the 1980s.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Further tests within 24 hours of the initial diagnosis revealed that Ashe had AIDS, but he did not tell the public about his diagnosis until April 1992.
[src:infection/aids-p02] He died as a result on February 6, 1993, aged 49.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Therese Frare's photograph of gay activist David Kirby, as he lay dying from AIDS while surrounded by family, was taken in April 1990.
[src:infection/aids-p02] *Life* magazine said the photo became the one image "most powerfully identified with the HIV/AIDS epidemic." The photo was displayed in *Life*, was the winner of the World Press Photo, and acquired worldwide notoriety after being used in a United Colors of Benetton advertising campaign in 1992.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Many famous artists and AIDS activists such as Larry Kramer, Diamanda Galás and Rosa von Praunheim campaign for AIDS education and the rights of those affected.
[src:infection/aids-p02] These artists worked with various media formats.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Criminal transmission of HIV is the intentional or reckless infection of a person with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
[src:infection/aids-p02] Some countries or jurisdictions, including some areas of the United States, have laws that criminalize HIV transmission or exposure.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Others may charge the accused under laws enacted before the HIV pandemic.
[src:infection/aids-p02] In 1996, Ugandan-born Canadian Johnson Aziga was diagnosed with HIV; he subsequently had unprotected sex with eleven women without disclosing his diagnosis.
[src:infection/aids-p02] By 2003, seven had contracted HIV; two died from complications related to AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Aziga was convicted of first-degree murder and sentenced to life imprisonment.
[src:infection/aids-p02] There are many misconceptions about HIV and AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Three misconceptions are that AIDS can spread through casual contact, that sexual intercourse with a virgin will cure AIDS, and that HIV can infect only gay men and drug users.
[src:infection/aids-p02] In 2014, some among the British public wrongly thought one could get HIV from kissing (16%), sharing a glass (5%), spitting (16%), a public toilet seat (4%), and coughing or sneezing (5%).
[src:infection/aids-p02] Other misconceptions are that any act of anal intercourse between two uninfected gay men can lead to HIV infection, and that open discussion of HIV and homosexuality in schools will lead to increased rates of AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p02] A small group of individuals continue to dispute the connection between HIV and AIDS, the existence of HIV itself, or the validity of HIV testing and treatment methods.
[src:infection/aids-p02] These claims, known as AIDS denialism, have been examined and rejected by the scientific community.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Several discredited conspiracy theories have held that HIV was created by scientists, either inadvertently or deliberately.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Operation INFEKTION was a worldwide Soviet active measures operation to spread the claim that the United States had created HIV/AIDS.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Surveys show that a significant number of people believed—and continue to believe—in such claims.
[src:infection/aids-p02] HIV/AIDS research includes all medical research which attempts to prevent, treat, or cure HIV/AIDS, along with fundamental research about the nature of HIV as an infectious agent, and about AIDS as the disease caused by HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Many governments and research institutions participate in HIV/AIDS research.
[src:infection/aids-p02] This research includes behavioral health interventions such as sex education, and drug development, such as research into microbicides for sexually transmitted diseases, HIV vaccines, and antiretroviral drugs.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Other medical research areas include the topics of pre-exposure prophylaxis, post-exposure prophylaxis, and circumcision and HIV.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Public health officials, researchers, and programs can gain a more comprehensive picture of the barriers they face, and the efficacy of current approaches to HIV treatment and prevention, by tracking standard HIV indicators.
[src:infection/aids-p02] Use of common indicators is an increasing focus of development organizations and researchers.
[src:infection/atc-code-j07] National versions of the ATC classification may include additional codes not present in this list, which follows the WHO version.
[src:infection/infection-p01] An **infection** is the invasion of tissues by pathogens, their multiplication, and the reaction of host tissues to the infectious agent and the toxins they produce.
[src:infection/infection-p01] An **infectious disease** is an illness resulting from an infection, and some infectious diseases are also communicable (transmissible).
[src:infection/infection-p01] Infections can be caused by a wide range of pathogens, most prominently bacteria and viruses.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Hosts can fight infections using their immune systems.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Mammalian hosts react to infections with an innate response, often involving inflammation, followed by an adaptive response.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Treatment for infections depends on the type of pathogen involved.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Infectious diseases remain a significant global health concern; communicable, maternal, neonatal, and nutritional diseases together accounted for an estimated 18.6% of global deaths in 2017.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The branch of medicine that focuses on infections is referred to as infectious diseases.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The signs and symptoms of an infection depend on the type of disease.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some signs of infection affect the whole body generally, such as fatigue, loss of appetite, weight loss, fevers, night sweats, chills, aches and pains.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Others are specific to individual body parts, such as skin rashes, coughing, or a runny nose.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In certain cases, infectious diseases may be asymptomatic for much or even all of their course in a given host.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In the latter case, the disease may only be defined as a "disease" (which by definition means an illness) in hosts who secondarily become ill after contact with an asymptomatic carrier.
[src:infection/infection-p01] An infection is not synonymous with an infectious disease, as some infections do not cause illness in a host.
[src:infection/infection-p01] As bacterial and viral infections can both cause the same kinds of symptoms, it can be difficult to distinguish which is the cause of a specific infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Distinguishing the two is important, since viral infections cannot be cured by antibiotics whereas bacterial infections can.
[src:infection/infection-p01] There is a general chain of events that applies to infections, sometimes called the **chain of infection** or **transmission chain**.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The chain of events involves several steps – which include the infectious agent, reservoir, entering a susceptible host, exit and transmission to new hosts.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Each of the links must be present in a chronological order for an infection to develop.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Understanding these steps helps health care workers target the infection and prevent it from occurring in the first place.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Infection begins when an organism successfully enters the body, grows and multiplies.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Those with compromised or weakened immune systems have an increased susceptibility to chronic or persistent infections.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Individuals who have a suppressed immune system are particularly susceptible to opportunistic infections.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Entrance to the host at host–pathogen interface, generally occurs through the mucosa in orifices like the oral cavity, nose, eyes, genitalia, anus, or the microbe can enter through open wounds.
[src:infection/infection-p01] While a few organisms can grow at the initial site of entry, many migrate and cause systemic infection in different organs.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some pathogens grow within the host cells (intracellular) whereas others grow freely in bodily fluids.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Wound colonization refers to non-replicating microorganisms within the wound, while in infected wounds, replicating organisms exist and tissue is injured.
[src:infection/infection-p01] All multicellular organisms are colonized to some degree by extrinsic organisms, and the vast majority of these exist in either a mutualistic or commensal relationship with the host.
[src:infection/infection-p01] An example of the former is the anaerobic bacteria species, which colonizes the mammalian colon, and an example of the latter are the various species of staphylococcus that exist on human skin.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Neither of these colonizations are considered infections.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The difference between an infection and a colonization is often only a matter of circumstance.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Non-pathogenic organisms can become pathogenic given specific conditions, and even the most virulent organism requires certain circumstances to cause a compromising infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some colonizing bacteria, such as *Corynebacteria sp.* and *Viridans streptococci*, prevent the adhesion and colonization of pathogenic bacteria and thus have a symbiotic relationship with the host, preventing infection and speeding wound healing.
[src:infection/infection-p01] As an example, several staphylococcal species remain harmless on the skin, but, when present in a normally sterile space, such as in the capsule of a joint or the peritoneum, multiply without resistance and cause harm.
[src:infection/infection-p01] An interesting fact that gas chromatography–mass spectrometry, 16S ribosomal RNA analysis, omics, and other advanced technologies have made more apparent to humans in recent decades is that microbial colonization is very common even in environments that humans think of as being nearly sterile.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Because it is normal to have bacterial colonization, it is difficult to know which chronic wounds can be classified as infected and how much risk of progression exists.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Despite the huge number of wounds seen in clinical practice, there are limited quality data for evaluated symptoms and signs.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A review of chronic wounds in the Journal of the American Medical Association's "Rational Clinical Examination Series" quantified the importance of increased pain as an indicator of infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The review showed that the most useful finding was an increase in the level of pain (likelihood ratio range, 11–20), which makes infection much more likely; the absence of pain (likelihood ratio range, 0.64–0.88) does not rule out infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Disease can arise if the host's protective immune mechanisms are compromised and the organism inflicts damage on the host.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Microorganisms can cause tissue damage by releasing a variety of toxins or destructive enzymes.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For example, *Clostridium tetani* releases a toxin that paralyzes muscles, and staphylococcus releases toxins that produce shock and sepsis.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Not all infectious agents cause disease in all hosts.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For example, less than 5% of individuals infected with polio develop disease.
[src:infection/infection-p01] On the other hand, some infectious agents are highly virulent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The prion causing mad cow disease and Creutzfeldt–Jakob disease invariably kills all animals and people that are infected.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Persistent infections occur because the body is unable to clear the organism after the initial infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Persistent infections are characterized by the continual presence of the infectious organism, often as latent infection with occasional recurrent relapses of active infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] There are some viruses that can maintain a persistent infection by infecting different cells of the body.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some viruses once acquired never leave the body.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A typical example is the herpes virus, which tends to hide in nerves and become reactivated when specific circumstances arise.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Persistent infections cause millions of deaths globally each year.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Chronic infections by parasites account for a high morbidity and mortality in many underdeveloped countries.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For infecting organisms to survive and repeat the infection cycle in other hosts, they (or their progeny) must leave an existing reservoir and cause infection elsewhere.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The relationship between *virulence versus transmissibility* is complex; with studies showing no clear relationships between the two.
[src:infection/infection-p01] There is still a small number of evidence that partially suggests a link between virulence and transmissibility.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Diagnosis of infectious disease sometimes involves identifying an infectious agent either directly or indirectly.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In practice most minor infectious diseases such as warts, cutaneous abscesses, respiratory system infections and diarrheal diseases are diagnosed by their clinical presentation and treated without knowledge of the specific causative agent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Conclusions about the cause of the disease are based upon the likelihood that a patient came in contact with a particular agent, the presence of a microbe in a community, and other epidemiological considerations.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Given sufficient effort, all known infectious agents can be specifically identified.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Diagnosis of infectious disease is nearly always initiated by medical history and physical examination.
[src:infection/infection-p01] More detailed identification techniques involve the culture of infectious agents isolated from a patient.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Culture allows identification of infectious organisms by examining their microscopic features, by detecting the presence of substances produced by pathogens, and by directly identifying an organism by its genotype.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Many infectious organisms are identified without culture and microscopy.
[src:infection/infection-p01] This is especially true for viruses, which cannot grow in culture.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For some suspected pathogens, doctors may conduct tests that examine a patient's blood or other body fluids for antigens or antibodies that indicate presence of a specific pathogen that the doctor suspects.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Other techniques (such as X-rays, CAT scans, PET scans or NMR) are used to produce images of internal abnormalities resulting from the growth of an infectious agent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The images are useful in detection of, for example, a bone abscess or a spongiform encephalopathy produced by a prion.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The benefits of identification, however, are often greatly outweighed by the cost, as often there is no specific treatment, the cause is obvious, or the outcome of an infection is likely to be benign.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The diagnosis is aided by the presenting symptoms in any individual with an infectious disease, yet it usually needs additional diagnostic techniques to confirm the suspicion.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some signs are specifically characteristic and indicative of a disease and are called pathognomonic signs; but these are rare.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In children the presence of cyanosis, rapid breathing, poor peripheral perfusion, or a petechial rash increases the risk of a serious infection by greater than 5 fold.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Other important indicators include parental concern, clinical instinct, and temperature greater than 40 °C.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Many diagnostic approaches depend on microbiological culture to isolate a pathogen from the appropriate clinical specimen.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In a microbial culture, a growth medium is provided for a specific agent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A sample taken from potentially diseased tissue or fluid is then tested for the presence of an infectious agent able to grow within that medium.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Many pathogenic bacteria are easily grown on nutrient agar, a form of solid medium that supplies carbohydrates and proteins necessary for growth, along with copious amounts of water.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A single bacterium will grow into a visible mound on the surface of the plate called a colony, which may be separated from other colonies or melded together into a "lawn".
[src:infection/infection-p01] The size, color, shape and form of a colony is characteristic of the bacterial species, its specific genetic makeup (its strain), and the environment that supports its growth.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Other ingredients are often added to the plate to aid in identification.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Plates may contain substances that permit the growth of some bacteria and not others, or that change color in response to certain bacteria and not others.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Bacteriological plates such as these are commonly used in the clinical identification of infectious bacterium.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Microbial culture may also be used in the identification of viruses: the medium, in this case, being cells grown in culture that the virus can infect, and then alter or kill.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In the case of viral identification, a region of dead cells results from viral growth, and is called a "plaque".
[src:infection/infection-p01] Eukaryotic parasites may also be grown in culture as a means of identifying a particular agent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In the absence of suitable plate culture techniques, some microbes require culture within live animals.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Bacteria such as *Mycobacterium leprae* and *Treponema pallidum* can be grown in animals, although serological and microscopic techniques make the use of live animals unnecessary.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Viruses are also usually identified using alternatives to growth in culture or animals.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some viruses may be grown in embryonated eggs.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Another useful identification method is Xenodiagnosis, or the use of a vector to support the growth of an infectious agent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Chagas disease is the most significant example, because it is difficult to directly demonstrate the presence of the causative agent, *Trypanosoma cruzi* in a patient, which therefore makes it difficult to definitively make a diagnosis.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In this case, xenodiagnosis involves the use of the vector of the Chagas agent *T. cruzi*, an uninfected triatomine bug, which takes a blood meal from a person suspected of having been infected.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The bug is later inspected for growth of *T. cruzi* within its gut.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Another principal tool in the diagnosis of infectious disease is microscopy.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Virtually all of the culture techniques discussed above rely, at some point, on microscopic examination for definitive identification of the infectious agent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Microscopy may be carried out with simple instruments, such as the compound light microscope, or with instruments as complex as an electron microscope.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Samples obtained from patients may be viewed directly under the light microscope, and can often rapidly lead to identification.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Microscopy is often also used in conjunction with biochemical staining techniques, and can be made exquisitely specific when used in combination with antibody based techniques.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For example, the use of antibodies made artificially fluorescent (fluorescently labeled antibodies) can be directed to bind to and identify a specific antigens present on a pathogen.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A fluorescence microscope is then used to detect fluorescently labeled antibodies bound to internalized antigens within clinical samples or cultured cells.
[src:infection/infection-p01] This technique is especially useful in the diagnosis of viral diseases, where the light microscope is incapable of identifying a virus directly.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Other microscopic procedures may also aid in identifying infectious agents.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Almost all cells readily stain with a number of basic dyes due to the electrostatic attraction between negatively charged cellular molecules and the positive charge on the dye.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A cell is normally transparent under a microscope, and using a stain increases the contrast of a cell with its background.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Staining a cell with a dye such as Giemsa stain or crystal violet allows a microscopist to describe its size, shape, internal and external components and its associations with other cells.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The response of bacteria to different staining procedures is used in the taxonomic classification of microbes as well.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Two methods, the Gram stain and the acid-fast stain, are the standard approaches used to classify bacteria and to diagnosis of disease.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The Gram stain identifies the bacterial groups Bacillota and Actinomycetota, both of which contain many significant human pathogens.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The acid-fast staining procedure identifies the Actinomycetota genera *Mycobacterium* and *Nocardia*.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Biochemical tests used in the identification of infectious agents include the detection of metabolic or enzymatic products characteristic of a particular infectious agent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Since bacteria ferment carbohydrates in patterns characteristic of their genus and species, the detection of fermentation products is commonly used in bacterial identification.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Acids, alcohols and gases are usually detected in these tests when bacteria are grown in selective liquid or solid media.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The isolation of enzymes from infected tissue can also provide the basis of a biochemical diagnosis of an infectious disease.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For example, humans can make neither RNA replicases nor reverse transcriptase, and the presence of these enzymes is characteristic of specific types of viral infections.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The ability of the viral protein hemagglutinin to bind red blood cells together into a detectable matrix may also be characterized as a biochemical test for viral infection, although strictly speaking hemagglutinin is not an *enzyme* and has no metabolic function.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Serological methods are highly sensitive, specific and often extremely rapid tests used to identify microorganisms.
[src:infection/infection-p01] These tests are based upon the ability of an antibody to bind specifically to an antigen.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The antigen, usually a protein or carbohydrate made by an infectious agent, is bound by the antibody.
[src:infection/infection-p01] This binding then sets off a chain of events that can be visibly obvious in various ways, dependent upon the test.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For example, "Strep throat" is often diagnosed within minutes, and is based on the appearance of antigens made by the causative agent, *S. pyogenes*, that is retrieved from a patient's throat with a cotton swab.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Serological tests, if available, are usually the preferred route of identification, however the tests are costly to develop and the reagents used in the test often require refrigeration.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some serological methods are extremely costly, although when commonly used, such as with the "strep test", they can be inexpensive.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Complex serological techniques have been developed into what are known as immunoassays.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Immunoassays can use the basic antibody–antigen binding as the basis to produce an electro-magnetic or particle radiation signal, which can be detected by some form of instrumentation.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Signal of unknowns can be compared to that of standards allowing quantitation of the target antigen.
[src:infection/infection-p01] To aid in the diagnosis of infectious diseases, immunoassays can detect or measure antigens from either infectious agents or proteins generated by an infected organism in response to a foreign agent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For example, immunoassay A may detect the presence of a surface protein from a virus particle.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Immunoassay B on the other hand may detect or measure antibodies produced by an organism's immune system that are made to neutralize and allow the destruction of the virus.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Instrumentation can be used to read extremely small signals created by secondary reactions linked to the antibody – antigen binding.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Instrumentation can control sampling, reagent use, reaction times, signal detection, calculation of results, and data management to yield a cost-effective automated process for diagnosis of infectious disease.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Technologies based upon the polymerase chain reaction (PCR) method will become nearly ubiquitous gold standards of diagnostics of the near future, for several reasons.
[src:infection/infection-p01] First, the catalog of infectious agents has grown to the point that virtually all of the significant infectious agents of the human population have been identified.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Second, an infectious agent must grow within the human body to cause disease; essentially it must amplify its own nucleic acids to cause a disease.
[src:infection/infection-p01] This amplification of nucleic acid in infected tissue offers an opportunity to detect the infectious agent by using PCR.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Third, the essential tools for directing PCR, primers, are derived from the genomes of infectious agents, and with time those genomes will be known if they are not already.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Thus, the technological ability to detect any infectious agent rapidly and specifically is currently available.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The only remaining blockades to the use of PCR as a standard tool of diagnosis are in its cost and application, neither of which is insurmountable.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The diagnosis of a few diseases will not benefit from the development of PCR methods, such as some of the clostridial diseases (tetanus and botulism).
[src:infection/infection-p01] These diseases are fundamentally biological poisonings by relatively small numbers of infectious bacteria that produce extremely potent neurotoxins.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A significant proliferation of the infectious agent does not occur, which limits the ability of PCR to detect the presence of any bacteria.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Given the wide range of bacterial, viral, fungal, protozoal, and helminthic pathogens that cause debilitating and life-threatening illnesses, the ability to quickly identify the cause of infection is important yet often challenging.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For example, more than half of cases of encephalitis, a severe illness affecting the brain, remain undiagnosed, despite extensive testing using the standard of care (microbiological culture) and state-of-the-art clinical laboratory methods.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Metagenomic sequencing-based diagnostic tests are currently being developed for clinical use and show promise as a sensitive, specific, and rapid way to diagnose infection using a single all-encompassing test.
[src:infection/infection-p01] This test is similar to current PCR tests; however, an untargeted whole genome amplification is used rather than primers for a specific infectious agent.
[src:infection/infection-p01] This amplification step is followed by next-generation sequencing or third-generation sequencing, alignment comparisons, and taxonomic classification using large databases of thousands of pathogen and commensal reference genomes.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Metagenomic sequencing could prove especially useful for diagnosis when the patient is immunocompromised.
[src:infection/infection-p01] An ever-wider array of infectious agents can cause serious harm to individuals with immunosuppression, so clinical screening must often be broader.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Additionally, the expression of symptoms is often atypical, making a clinical diagnosis based on presentation more difficult.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Thirdly, diagnostic methods that rely on the detection of antibodies are more likely to fail.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A rapid, sensitive, specific, and untargeted test for all known human pathogens that detects the presence of the organism's DNA rather than antibodies is therefore highly desirable.
[src:infection/infection-p01] There is usually an indication for a specific identification of an infectious agent only when such identification can aid in the treatment or prevention of the disease, or to advance knowledge of the course of an illness prior to the development of effective therapeutic or preventative measures.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For example, in the early 1980s, prior to the appearance of AZT for the treatment of AIDS, the course of the disease was closely followed by monitoring the composition of patient blood samples, even though the outcome would not offer the patient any further treatment options.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In part, these studies on the appearance of HIV in specific communities permitted the advancement of hypotheses as to the route of transmission of the virus.
[src:infection/infection-p01] By understanding how the disease was transmitted, resources could be targeted to the communities at greatest risk in campaigns aimed at reducing the number of new infections.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The specific serological diagnostic identification, and later genotypic or molecular identification, of HIV also enabled the development of hypotheses as to the temporal and geographical origins of the virus, as well as a myriad of other hypothesis.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The development of molecular diagnostic tools have enabled physicians and researchers to monitor the efficacy of treatment with anti-retroviral drugs.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Molecular diagnostics are now commonly used to identify HIV in healthy people long before the onset of illness and have been used to demonstrate the existence of people who are genetically resistant to HIV infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Thus, while there still is no cure for AIDS, there is great therapeutic and predictive benefit to identifying the virus and monitoring the virus levels within the blood of infected individuals, both for the patient and for the community at large.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Symptomatic infections are *apparent* and *clinical*, whereas an infection that is active but does not produce noticeable symptoms may be called *inapparent,* *silent,* *subclinical*, or occult.
[src:infection/infection-p01] An infection that is inactive or dormant is called a *latent infection*.
[src:infection/infection-p01] An example of a latent bacterial infection is latent tuberculosis.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some viral infections can also be latent, examples of latent viral infections are any of those from the *Herpesviridae* family.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The word *infection* can denote any presence of a particular pathogen at all (no matter how little) but also is often used in a sense implying a *clinically apparent* infection (in other words, a case of infectious disease).
[src:infection/infection-p01] Different terms are used to describe how and where infections present over time.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In an *acute* infection, symptoms develop rapidly; its course can either be rapid or protracted.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In *chronic* infection, symptoms usually develop gradually over weeks or months and are slow to resolve.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In *subacute* infections, symptoms take longer to develop than in acute infections but arise more quickly than those of chronic infections.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A *focal* infection is an initial site of infection from which organisms travel via the bloodstream to another area of the body.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Among the many varieties of microorganisms, relatively few cause disease in otherwise healthy individuals.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Infectious disease results from the interplay between those few pathogens and the defenses of the hosts they infect.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The appearance and severity of disease resulting from any pathogen depend upon the ability of that pathogen to damage the host as well as the ability of the host to resist the pathogen.
[src:infection/infection-p01] However, a host's immune system can also cause damage to the host itself in an attempt to control the infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Clinicians, therefore, classify infectious microorganisms or microbes according to the status of host defenses – either as *primary pathogens* or as *opportunistic pathogens*.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Primary pathogens cause disease as a result of their presence or activity within the normal, healthy host, and their intrinsic virulence (the severity of the disease they cause) is, in part, a necessary consequence of their need to reproduce and spread.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Many of the most common primary pathogens of humans only infect humans, however, many serious diseases are caused by organisms acquired from the environment or that infect non-human hosts.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Opportunistic pathogens can cause an infectious disease in a host with depressed resistance (immunodeficiency) or if they have unusual access to the inside of the body (for example, via trauma).
[src:infection/infection-p01] Primary pathogens may also cause more severe disease in a host with depressed resistance than would normally occur in an immunosufficient host.
[src:infection/infection-p01] While a primary infection can practically be viewed as the root cause of an individual's current health problem, a secondary infection is a sequela or complication of that root cause.
[src:infection/infection-p01] For example, an infection due to a burn or penetrating trauma (the root cause) is a secondary infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Primary pathogens often cause primary infection and often cause secondary infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Usually, opportunistic infections are viewed as secondary infections (because immunodeficiency or injury was the predisposing factor).
[src:infection/infection-p01] Other types of infection consist of mixed, iatrogenic, nosocomial, and community-acquired infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A mixed infection is an infection that is caused by two or more pathogens.
[src:infection/infection-p01] An example of this is appendicitis, which is caused by *Bacteroides fragilis* and *Escherichia coli*.
[src:infection/infection-p01] This type of infection is one that is transmitted from a health care worker to a patient.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A nosocomial infection is also one that occurs in a health care setting.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Nosocomial infections are those that are acquired during a hospital stay.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Lastly, a community-acquired infection is one in which the infection is acquired from a whole community.
[src:infection/infection-p01] These postulates were first used in the discovery that Mycobacteria species cause tuberculosis.
[src:infection/infection-p01] However, Koch's postulates cannot usually be tested in modern practice for ethical reasons.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Proving them would require experimental infection of a healthy individual with a pathogen produced as a pure culture.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Conversely, even clearly infectious diseases do not always meet the infectious criteria; for example, *Treponema pallidum*, the causative spirochete of syphilis, cannot be cultured *in vitro* – however the organism can be cultured in rabbit testes.
[src:infection/infection-p01] It is less clear that a pure culture comes from an animal source serving as host than it is when derived from microbes derived from plate culture.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Epidemiology, or the study and analysis of who, why and where disease occurs, and what determines whether various populations have a disease, is another important tool used to understand infectious disease.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Epidemiologists may determine differences among groups within a population, such as whether certain age groups have a greater or lesser rate of infection; whether groups living in different neighborhoods are more likely to be infected; and by other factors, such as gender and race.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Researchers also may assess whether a disease outbreak is sporadic, or just an occasional occurrence; endemic, with a steady level of regular cases occurring in a region; epidemic, with a fast arising, and unusually high number of cases in a region; or pandemic, which is a global epidemic.
[src:infection/infection-p01] If the cause of the infectious disease is unknown, epidemiology can be used to assist with tracking down the sources of infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Infectious diseases are sometimes called contagious diseases when they are easily transmitted by contact with an ill person or their secretions (e.g., influenza).
[src:infection/infection-p01] Thus, a contagious disease is a subset of infectious disease that is especially infective or easily transmitted.
[src:infection/infection-p01] All contagious diseases are infectious, but not vice versa.
[src:infection/infection-p01] However, this specialized connotation of the word "contagious" and "contagious disease" (easy transmissibility) is not always respected in popular use.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Infectious diseases are commonly transmitted from person to person through direct contact.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The types of direct contact are through person to person and droplet spread.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Indirect contact such as airborne transmission, contaminated objects, food and drinking water, animal person contact, animal reservoirs, insect bites, and environmental reservoirs are another way infectious diseases are transmitted.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The basic reproduction number of an infectious disease measures how easily it spreads through direct or indirect contact.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In addition, locations of inflammation where infection is the most common cause include pneumonia, meningitis and salpingitis.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Techniques like hand washing, wearing gowns, and wearing face masks can help prevent infections from being passed from one person to another.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Aseptic technique was introduced in medicine and surgery in the late 19th century and greatly reduced the incidence of infections caused by surgery.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Frequent hand washing remains the most important defense against the spread of unwanted organisms.
[src:infection/infection-p01] There are other forms of prevention such as avoiding the use of illicit drugs, using a condom, wearing gloves, and having a healthy lifestyle with a balanced diet and regular exercise.
[src:infection/infection-p01] One of the ways to prevent or slow down the transmission of infectious diseases is to recognize the different characteristics of various diseases.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some critical disease characteristics that should be evaluated include virulence, distance traveled by those affected, and level of contagiousness.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The human strains of Ebola virus, for example, incapacitate those infected extremely quickly and kill them soon after.
[src:infection/infection-p01] As a result, those affected by this disease do not have the opportunity to travel very far from the initial infection zone.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Also, this virus must spread through skin lesions or permeable membranes such as the eye.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Thus, the initial stage of Ebola is not very contagious since its victims experience only internal hemorrhaging.
[src:infection/infection-p01] As a result of the above features, the spread of Ebola is very rapid and usually stays within a relatively confined geographical area.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In contrast, the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) kills its victims very slowly by attacking their immune system.
[src:infection/infection-p01] As a result, many of its victims transmit the virus to other individuals before even realizing that they are carrying the disease.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Also, the relatively low virulence allows its victims to travel long distances, increasing the likelihood of an epidemic.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Another effective way to decrease the transmission rate of infectious diseases is to recognize the effects of small-world networks.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In epidemics, there are often extensive interactions within hubs or groups of infected individuals and other interactions within discrete hubs of susceptible individuals.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Despite the low interaction between discrete hubs, the disease can jump and spread in a susceptible hub via a single or few interactions with an infected hub.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Thus, infection rates in small-world networks can be reduced somewhat if interactions between individuals within infected hubs are eliminated (Figure 1).
[src:infection/infection-p01] However, infection rates can be drastically reduced if the main focus is on the prevention of transmission jumps between hubs.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The use of needle exchange programs in areas with a high density of drug users with HIV is an example of the successful implementation of this treatment method.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Another example is the use of ring culling or vaccination of potentially susceptible livestock in adjacent farms to prevent the spread of the foot-and-mouth virus in 2001.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A general method to prevent transmission of vector-borne pathogens is pest control.
[src:infection/infection-p01] In cases where infection is merely suspected, individuals may be quarantined until the incubation period has passed and the disease manifests itself or the person remains healthy.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Groups may undergo quarantine, or in the case of communities, a cordon sanitaire may be imposed to prevent infection from spreading beyond the community, or in the case of protective sequestration, into a community.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Public health authorities may implement other forms of social distancing, such as school closings, lockdowns or temporary restrictions (e.g. circuit breakers) to control an epidemic.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Infection with most pathogens does not result in death of the host and the offending organism is ultimately cleared after the symptoms of the disease have waned.
[src:infection/infection-p01] This process requires immune mechanisms to kill or inactivate the inoculum of the pathogen.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Specific acquired immunity against infectious diseases may be mediated by antibodies and/or T lymphocytes.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The immune system response to a microorganism often causes symptoms such as a high fever and inflammation, and has the potential to be more devastating than direct damage caused by a microbe.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Resistance to infection (immunity) may be acquired following a disease, by asymptomatic carriage of the pathogen, by harboring an organism with a similar structure (crossreacting), or by vaccination.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Knowledge of the protective antigens and specific acquired host immune factors is more complete for primary pathogens than for opportunistic pathogens.
[src:infection/infection-p01] There is also the phenomenon of herd immunity which offers a measure of protection to those otherwise vulnerable people when a large enough proportion of the population has acquired immunity from certain infections.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Immune resistance to an infectious disease requires a critical level of either antigen-specific antibodies and/or T cells when the host encounters the pathogen.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Some individuals develop natural serum antibodies to the surface polysaccharides of some agents although they have had little or no contact with the agent, these natural antibodies confer specific protection to adults and are passively transmitted to newborns.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The organism that is the target of an infecting action of a specific infectious agent is called the host.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The host harboring an agent that is in a mature or sexually active stage phase is called the definitive host.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The intermediate host comes in contact during the larvae stage.
[src:infection/infection-p01] A host can be anything living and can attain to asexual and sexual reproduction.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The clearance of the pathogens, either treatment-induced or spontaneous, can be influenced by the genetic variants carried by individual patients.
[src:infection/infection-p01] This finding, originally reported in *Nature*, showed that genotype 1 hepatitis C patients carrying certain genetic variant alleles near the IL28B gene are more likely to achieve a sustained virological response after treatment than others.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Later report from *Nature* demonstrated that the same genetic variants are also associated with the natural clearance of the genotype 1 hepatitis C virus.
[src:infection/infection-p01] When infection attacks the body, *anti-infective* drugs can suppress the infection.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Several broad types of anti-infective drugs exist, depending on the type of organism targeted; they include antibacterial (antibiotic; including antitubercular), antiviral, antifungal and antiparasitic (including antiprotozoal and antihelminthic) agents.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Depending on the severity and the type of infection, the antibiotic may be given by mouth or by injection, or may be applied topically.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Severe infections of the brain are usually treated with intravenous antibiotics.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Sometimes, multiple antibiotics are used in case there is resistance to one antibiotic.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Antibiotics only work for bacteria and do not affect viruses.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Antibiotics work by slowing down the multiplication of bacteria or killing the bacteria.
[src:infection/infection-p01] The most common classes of antibiotics used in medicine include penicillin, cephalosporins, aminoglycosides, macrolides, quinolones and tetracyclines.
[src:infection/infection-p01] Not all infections require treatment, and for many self-limiting infections the treatment may cause more side-effects than benefits.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Pandemics such as COVID-19 show that people dramatically differ in their susceptibility to infection.
[src:infection/infection-p02] This may be because of general health, age, or their immune status, e.g. when they have been infected previously.
[src:infection/infection-p02] However, it also has become clear that there are genetic factors which determine susceptibility to infection.
[src:infection/infection-p02] For instance, up to 40% of SARS-CoV-2 infections may be asymptomatic, suggesting that many people are naturally protected from disease.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Large genetic studies have defined risk factors for severe SARS-CoV-2 infections, and genome sequences from 659 patients with severe COVID-19 revealed genetic variants that appear to be associated with life-threatening disease.
[src:infection/infection-p02] One gene identified in these studies is type I interferon (IFN).
[src:infection/infection-p02] Autoantibodies against type I IFNs were found in up to 13.7% of patients with life-threatening COVID-19, indicating that a complex interaction between genetics and the immune system is important for natural resistance to Covid.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Similarly, mutations in the ERAP2 gene, encoding endoplasmic reticulum aminopeptidase 2, seem to increase the susceptibility to the plague, the disease caused by an infection with the bacteria *Yersinia pestis*.
[src:infection/infection-p02] People who inherited two copies of a complete variant of the gene were twice as likely to have survived the plague as those who inherited two copies of a truncated variant.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Susceptibility also determined the epidemiology of infection, given that different populations have different genetic and environmental conditions that affect infections.
[src:infection/infection-p02] An estimated 1,680 million people died of infectious diseases in the 20th century and about 10 million in 2010.
[src:infection/infection-p02] The World Health Organization collects information on global deaths by International Classification of Disease (ICD) code categories.
[src:infection/infection-p02] The following table lists the top infectious disease by number of deaths in 2002.
[src:infection/infection-p02] The top three single agent/disease killers are HIV/AIDS, TB and malaria.
[src:infection/infection-p02] While the number of deaths due to nearly every disease have decreased, deaths due to HIV/AIDS have increased fourfold.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Childhood diseases include pertussis, poliomyelitis, diphtheria, measles and tetanus.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Children also make up a large percentage of lower respiratory and diarrheal deaths.
[src:infection/infection-p02] In 2012, approximately 3.1 million people have died due to lower respiratory infections, making it the number 4 leading cause of death in the world.
[src:infection/infection-p02] With their potential for unpredictable and explosive impacts, infectious diseases have been major actors in human history.
[src:infection/infection-p02] A pandemic (or global epidemic) is a disease that affects people over an extensive geographical area.
[src:infection/infection-p02] In most cases, microorganisms live in harmony with their hosts via mutual or commensal interactions.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Diseases can emerge when existing parasites become pathogenic or when new pathogenic parasites enter a new host.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Human activity is involved with many emerging infectious diseases, such as environmental change enabling a parasite to occupy new niches.
[src:infection/infection-p02] When that happens, a pathogen that had been confined to a remote habitat has a wider distribution and possibly a new host organism.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Parasites jumping from nonhuman to human hosts are known as zoonoses.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Under disease invasion, when a parasite invades a new host species, it may become pathogenic in the new host.
[src:infection/infection-p02] In Antiquity, the Greek historian Thucydides (c.
[src:infection/infection-p02] 400 BCE) was the first person to write, in his account of the plague of Athens, that diseases could spread from an infected person to others.
[src:infection/infection-p02] In his *On the Different Types of Fever* (c.
[src:infection/infection-p02] 175 AD), the Greco-Roman physician Galen speculated that plagues were spread by "certain seeds of plague", which were present in the air.
[src:infection/infection-p02] A basic form of contagion theory was proposed by Persian physician Ibn Sina (known as Avicenna in Europe) in *The Canon of Medicine* (1025), which later became the most authoritative medical textbook in Europe up until the 16th century.
[src:infection/infection-p02] In Book IV of the *Canon*, Ibn Sina discussed epidemics, outlining the classical miasma theory and attempting to blend it with his own early contagion theory.
[src:infection/infection-p02] He mentioned that people can transmit disease to others by breath, noted contagion with tuberculosis, and discussed the transmission of disease through water and dirt.
[src:infection/infection-p02] The concept of invisible contagion was later discussed by several Islamic scholars in the Ayyubid Sultanate who referred to them as *najasat* ("impure substances").
[src:infection/infection-p02] The fiqh scholar Ibn al-Haj al-Abdari (c.
[src:infection/infection-p02] 1250–1336), while discussing Islamic diet and hygiene, gave warnings about how contagion can contaminate water, food, and garments, and could spread through the water supply, and may have implied contagion to be unseen particles.
[src:infection/infection-p02] When the Black Death bubonic plague reached Al-Andalus in the 14th century, the Arab physicians Ibn Khatima (c.
[src:infection/infection-p02] 1369) and Ibn al-Khatib (1313–1374) hypothesised that infectious diseases were caused by "minute bodies" and described how they can be transmitted through garments, vessels and earrings.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Ideas of contagion became more popular in Europe during the Renaissance, particularly through the writing of the Italian physician Girolamo Fracastoro.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Anton van Leeuwenhoek (1632–1723) advanced the science of microscopy by being the first to observe microorganisms, allowing for easy visualization of bacteria.
[src:infection/infection-p02] In the mid-19th century John Snow and William Budd did important work demonstrating the contagiousness of typhoid and cholera through contaminated water.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Both are credited with decreasing epidemics of cholera in their towns by implementing measures to prevent contamination of water.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Louis Pasteur proved beyond doubt that certain diseases are caused by infectious agents, and developed a vaccine for rabies.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Robert Koch provided the study of infectious diseases with a scientific basis known as Koch's postulates.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Edward Jenner, Jonas Salk and Albert Sabin developed effective vaccines for smallpox and polio, which would later result in the eradication and near-eradication of these diseases, respectively.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Alexander Fleming discovered the world's first antibiotic, penicillin, which Florey and Chain then developed.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Gerhard Domagk developed sulphonamides, the first broad spectrum synthetic antibacterial drugs.
[src:infection/infection-p02] The medical treatment of infectious diseases falls into the medical field of Infectious Disease and in some cases the study of propagation pertains to the field of Epidemiology.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Generally, infections are initially diagnosed by primary care physicians or internal medicine specialists.
[src:infection/infection-p02] For example, an "uncomplicated" pneumonia will generally be treated by the internist or the pulmonologist (lung physician).
[src:infection/infection-p02] The work of the infectious diseases specialist therefore entails working with both patients and general practitioners, as well as laboratory scientists, immunologists, bacteriologists and other specialists.
[src:infection/infection-p02] According to the *parasite-stress theory of sociality*, examined in a 2009 review by Nettle, several studies have reported associations between regional pathogen load and aspects of human social behavior.
[src:infection/infection-p02] They attribute these patterns to strategies that may limit pathogen transmission or offset higher mortality.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Nettle's review notes that alternative explanations exist for several of these associations, and that some of those alternative factors may themselves ultimately trace back to pathogen load.
[src:infection/infection-p02] This body of research is largely correlational and is best understood as a proposed explanatory framework rather than an established causal mechanism.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Evidence of infection in fossil remains is a subject of interest for paleopathologists, scientists who study occurrences of injuries and illness in extinct life forms.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Signs of infection have been discovered in the bones of carnivorous dinosaurs.
[src:infection/infection-p02] When present, however, these infections seem to tend to be confined to only small regions of the body.
[src:infection/infection-p02] A skull attributed to the early carnivorous dinosaur *Herrerasaurus ischigualastensis* exhibits pit-like wounds surrounded by swollen and porous bone.
[src:infection/infection-p02] The unusual texture of the bone around the wounds suggests they were affected by a short-lived, non-lethal infection.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Scientists who studied the skull speculated that the bite marks were received in a fight with another *Herrerasaurus*.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Other carnivorous dinosaurs with documented evidence of infection include *Acrocanthosaurus*, *Allosaurus*, *Tyrannosaurus* and a tyrannosaur from the Kirtland Formation.
[src:infection/infection-p02] The infections from both tyrannosaurs were received by being bitten during a fight, like the *Herrerasaurus* specimen.
[src:infection/infection-p02] A 2006 Space Shuttle experiment found that *Salmonella typhimurium*, a bacterium that can cause food poisoning, became more virulent when cultivated in space.
[src:infection/infection-p02] On April 29, 2013, scientists in Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, funded by NASA, reported that, during spaceflight on the International Space Station, microbes seem to adapt to the space environment in ways "not observed on Earth" and in ways that "can lead to increases in growth and virulence".
[src:infection/infection-p02] More recently, in 2017, bacteria were found to be more resistant to antibiotics and to thrive in the near-weightlessness of space.
[src:infection/infection-p02] Microorganisms have been observed to survive the vacuum of outer space.
